{"title_page": "S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s Dam", "text_new": "The '''S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s Dam''' was expected to be the second largest hydroelectric in Brazil, after Belo Monte.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/22/brazil-amazon-dam-project-suspended-indigenous-munduruku-sao-luiz-do-tapajos|title=Brazil Amazon dam project suspended over concerns for indigenous people &#124; World news &#124; The Guardian|publisher=theguardian.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> It would have an installed capacity of 8,040 MW and its reservoir would cover about 400&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> in the [[Tapaj\u00f3s]] river basin.<ref>http://www.greenpeace.org/international/Global/brasil/documentos/2016/Greenpeace_Damning_The_Amazon-The_Risky_Business_Of_Hydropower_In_The_Amazon-2016.pdf</ref>\n\nThe plant would have been part of the proposed {{convert|12,000|MW}} [[Tapaj\u00f3s hydroelectric complex]] on the Tapajos and [[Jamanxim River|Jamanxim]] rivers.\nOthers are the [[Jatob\u00e1 Hydroelectric Power Plant|Jatob\u00e1]], [[Cachoeira dos Patos Dam|Cachoeira dos Patos]], [[Jamanxim Dam|Jamanxim]] and [[Cachoeira do Cai Dam|Cachoeira do Cai]] dams, all in Par\u00e1 state.<ref>{{citation|work=Hydro World|publisher=PennWell Corporation|ref={{harvid|Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos...}}\n |title=Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos hydro project|location=Brasilia|date=17 September 2014\n |url=http://www.hydroworld.com/articles/2014/09/brazil-sets-concession-auction-for-8-040-mw-sao-luiz-do-tapajos-hydro-project.html|accessdate=2017-02-13}}</ref>\nIn April 2016 [[Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources|IBAMA]] suspended the environmental licensing process for the dam due to its expected impacts on indigenous and river communities.<ref name=\"mongabay\">{{cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2016/04/amazon-mega-dam-suspended-hope-indigenous-people-biodiversity/|title=Amazon mega-dam suspended, providing hope for indigenous people and biodiversity &#8211; Conservation news|publisher=news.mongabay.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> In August that year, [[Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources|IBAMA]] finally announced the official cancellation of the project's environmental license, which effectively stopped the dam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mongabay.com/2016/08/environmental-licence-for-sao-luiz-do-tapajos-hydroelectric-dam-denied/|title=Environmental licence for S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s hydroelectric dam denied|date=2016-08-04|website=Conservation news|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-08}}</ref>\n\nThe conflict around the S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s mega dam has been referred as the next battle over saving the Amazon, as a result of its controversy involving Indigenous communities, the Brazilian government, large multinationals and international environmental organizations.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/04/15/this-will-be-the-next-battle-over-saving-the-amazon/|title=This will be the next battle over saving the Amazon - The Washington Post|publisher=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> Critics say the project will further result in deforestation and harm to the region's [[biodiversity]], affecting the migratory movements of several species of ornamental fish and destroying nests of [[Macaw]].<ref>[http://noticias.bol.uol.com.br/ciencia/2010/05/15/usinas-hidreletricas-no-rio-tapajos-alagarao-areas-protegidas.jhtm Usinas hidrel\u00e9tricas no Rio Tapaj\u00f3s alagar\u00e3o \u00e1reas protegidas]. Folha Online</ref>\n\n== Licensing process ==\nThe Brazilian environmental agency [[Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources|IBAMA]] first decided to suspend and ultimately cancel the environmental licensing process for the Tapaj\u00f3s mega dam in 2016, following a report published by the Brazilian bureau for Indigenous Affairs [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional do \u00cdndio|FUNAI]]. The report points out the infeasibility of the project from an indigenous perspective, since it would affect the land of the local [[Munduruku]] people. In its report, FUNAI recommends the demarcation of 1,780 square kilometers (687 square miles)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2016/04/amazon-mega-dam-suspended-hope-indigenous-people-biodiversity/|title=Amazon mega-dam suspended, providing hope for indigenous people and biodiversity|website=Conservation news|publisher=Mongabay|language=en-US|accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref> of Munduruku land, the [[Sawr\u00e9 Muybu Indigenous Territory]], in the vicinity of the proposed mega dam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/resources/11450|title=Brazil Suspends Licensing of Controversial Amazon Dam|website=International Rivers|accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Brazil|Water|Renewable energy}}}}\n\n{{Coord|4|36|13.4|S|56|17|04.2|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sao Luiz do Tapajos Dam}}\n[[Category:Dams in Par\u00e1]]\n[[Category:Dam controversies]]\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Proposed dams]]\n[[Category:Proposed hydroelectric power stations]]\n", "text_old": "The '''S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s Dam''' was expected to be the second largest hydroelectric in Brazil, after Belo Monte.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/22/brazil-amazon-dam-project-suspended-indigenous-munduruku-sao-luiz-do-tapajos|title=Brazil Amazon dam project suspended over concerns for indigenous people &#124; World news &#124; The Guardian|publisher=theguardian.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> It would have an installed capacity of 8,040 MW and its reservoir would cover about 400&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> in the [[Tapaj\u00f3s]] river basin.<ref>http://www.greenpeace.org/international/Global/brasil/documentos/2016/Greenpeace_Damning_The_Amazon-The_Risky_Business_Of_Hydropower_In_The_Amazon-2016.pdf</ref>\n\nThe plant would have been part of the proposed {{convert|12,000|MW}} [[Tapaj\u00f3s hydroelectric complex]] on the Tapajos and [[Jamanxim River|Jamanxim]] rivers.\nOthers are the [[Jatob\u00e1 Hydroelectric Power Plant|Jatob\u00e1]], [[Cachoeira dos Patos Dam|Cachoeira dos Patos]], [[Jamanxim Dam|Jamanxim]] and [[Cachoeira do Cai Dam|Cachoeira do Cai]] dams, all in Par\u00e1 state.<ref>{{citation|work=Hydro World|publisher=PennWell Corporation|ref={{harvid|Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos...}}\n |title=Brazil sets concession auction for 8,040-MW Sao Luiz do Tapajos hydro project|location=Brasilia|date=17 September 2014\n |url=http://www.hydroworld.com/articles/2014/09/brazil-sets-concession-auction-for-8-040-mw-sao-luiz-do-tapajos-hydro-project.html|accessdate=2017-02-13}}</ref>\nIn April 2016 [[Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources|IBAMA]] suspended the environmental licensing process for the dam due to its expected impacts on indigenous and river communities.<ref name=\"mongabay\">{{cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2016/04/amazon-mega-dam-suspended-hope-indigenous-people-biodiversity/|title=Amazon mega-dam suspended, providing hope for indigenous people and biodiversity &#8211; Conservation news|publisher=news.mongabay.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> In August that year, [[Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources|IBAMA]] finally announced the official cancellation of the project's environmental license, which effectively stopped the dam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mongabay.com/2016/08/environmental-licence-for-sao-luiz-do-tapajos-hydroelectric-dam-denied/|title=Environmental licence for S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s hydroelectric dam denied|date=2016-08-04|website=Conservation news|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-08}}</ref>\n\nThe conflict around the S\u00e3o Luiz do Tapaj\u00f3s mega dam has been referred as the next battle over saving the Amazon, as a result of its controversy involving Indigenous communities, the Brazilian government, large multinationals and international environmental organizations.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/04/15/this-will-be-the-next-battle-over-saving-the-amazon/|title=This will be the next battle over saving the Amazon - The Washington Post|publisher=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> Critics say the project will further result in deforestation and harm to the region's [[biodiversity]], affecting the migratory movements of several species of ornamental fish and destroying nests of [[Macaw]].<ref>[http://noticias.bol.uol.com.br/ciencia/2010/05/15/usinas-hidreletricas-no-rio-tapajos-alagarao-areas-protegidas.jhtm Usinas hidrel\u00e9tricas no Rio Tapaj\u00f3s alagar\u00e3o \u00e1reas protegidas]. Folha Online</ref>\n\n== Licensing process ==\nThe Brazilian environmental agency [[Brazilian Institute of Environment and Renewable Natural Resources|IBAMA]] first decided to suspend and ultimately cancel the environmental licensing process for the Tapaj\u00f3s mega dam in 2016, following a report published by the Brazilian bureau for Indigenous Affairs [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional do \u00cdndio|FUNAI]]. The report points out the infeasibility of the project from an indigenous perspective, since it would affect the land of the local [[Munduruku]] people. In its report, FUNAI recommends the demarcation of 1,780 square kilometers (687 square miles)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2016/04/amazon-mega-dam-suspended-hope-indigenous-people-biodiversity/|title=Amazon mega-dam suspended, providing hope for indigenous people and biodiversity|website=Conservation news|publisher=Mongabay|language=en-US|accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref> of Munduruku land, the [[Sawr\u00e9 Muybu Indigenous Territory]], in the vicinity of the proposed mega dam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/resources/11450|title=Brazil Suspends Licensing of Controversial Amazon Dam|website=International Rivers|accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Brazil|Water|Renewable energy}}}}\n\n{{Coord|4|36|13.4|S|56|17|04.2|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sao Luiz do Tapajos Dam}}\n[[Category:Dams in Par\u00e1]]\n[[Category:Dam controversies]]\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Cancelled dams]]\n[[Category:Cancelled hydroelectric power stations]]\n", "name_user": "Macquaria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cancellation of previous category change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A3o_Luiz_do_Tapaj%C3%B3s_Dam"}
{"title_page": "Postcards from the Edge (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1990 film by Mike Nichols}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Postcards from the Edge\n| image = Postcards_from_the_edge.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Mike Nichols]]\n| producer = [[John Calley]]<br />Mike Nichols\n| screenplay = [[Carrie Fisher]]\n| based on = {{based on|''[[Postcards from the Edge]]''|Carrie Fisher}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Meryl Streep]]\n* [[Shirley MacLaine]]\n* [[Dennis Quaid]]}}\n| music = [[Carly Simon]]\n| editing = [[Sam O'Steen]]\n| cinematography = [[Michael Ballhaus]]\n| studio = Columbia Pictures \n| distributor = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|1990|9|14}}\n| runtime = 101 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $22 million<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/07/movies/it-s-fade-out-for-the-cheap-film-as-hollywood-s-budgets-soar.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm | work=The New York Times | first=Aljean | last=Harmetz | title=It's Fade-Out for the Cheap Film As Hollywood's Budgets Soar | date=1989-12-07}}</ref>\n| gross = $39,071,603 (US)<ref name=\"Mojo\" />\n}}\n'''''Postcards from the Edge''''' is a 1990 American [[comedy-drama|comedy-drama film]] directed by [[Mike Nichols]]. The screenplay by [[Carrie Fisher]] is based on her 1987 semi-[[Autobiography|autobiographical]] [[Postcards from the Edge|novel of the same title]]. The film stars [[Meryl Streep]], [[Shirley MacLaine]], and [[Dennis Quaid]].\n\n==Plot==\nActress Suzanne Vale ([[Meryl Streep]]) is a recovering [[Addiction|drug addict]] trying to pick up the pieces of her acting [[career]] and get on with her life after being discharged from a [[drug rehabilitation|rehab center]] to kick a [[cocaine]]-[[Oxycodone/aspirin|Percodan]] habit; after overdosing while on a date, her mother admitted her to the rehab center from the emergency room. When she is ready to return to work her agent advises her the studio's insurance policy will cover her only if she lives with a \"responsible\" individual such as her mother Doris Mann ([[Shirley MacLaine]]). Suzanne is very reluctant to return to the woman from whom she struggled to escape for years after growing up in her shadow. The situation is not helped by the fact that Doris is very loud, competitive, manipulative, self-absorbed and given to offering her daughter unsolicited advice with insinuating value judgments while treating her like a child.\n\nProducer Jack Faulkner ([[Dennis Quaid]]) runs into Suzanne on the set and reveals that he is the one who drove her to the hospital during her last overdose, and the two kiss. Suzanne then agrees to go out with him. During the course of a passionate first date, he professes intense and eternal love for her and she believes every word is true. Suzanne's euphoria is short-lived, however; she subsequently learns from Evelyn Ames ([[Annette Bening]]), a [[Bit part|bit player]] in her latest film, that Jack is sleeping with Evelyn as well. Still dressed in the costume she wears as a uniformed cop in the [[Kitsch|schlock]] movie, Suzanne drives to Jack's house and confronts him. As their argument escalates, Jack implies that Suzanne was much more interesting when she was trying to function while [[Driving under the influence|under the influence]].\n\nAt home, Suzanne learns from Doris that Suzanne's sleazy business manager Marty Wiener has absconded with all her money. This leads to an argument between the two women, and Suzanne storms out to go to a [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|looping]] session. There the paternalistic director Lowell Kolchek ([[Gene Hackman]]) tells her he has more work for her as long as she can remain clean and sober.\n\nSuzanne arrives home and discovers that Doris has crashed her car into a tree after drinking too much wine (and [[Stolichnaya]] [[smoothie]]s). Suzanne rushes to her hospital bedside where the two have a heart-to-heart talk while Suzanne fixes her mother's makeup and arranges a scarf on her head to conceal the fact she bloodied her wig in the accident. Looking and feeling better, Doris musters her courage and faces the media waiting for her. Suzanne runs into Dr. Frankenthal ([[Richard Dreyfuss]]), who had pumped her stomach after her last overdose, and he invites her to see a movie with him. She declines, telling him she's not ready to date yet. Dr. Frankenthal tells her he's willing to wait until she is.\n\nIn the film's closing moments Suzanne performs \"I'm Checkin' Out,\" a foot-stomping [[Country music|Country Western]] number, for a scene in Lowell Kolchek's new film.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Suzanne Vale\n* [[Shirley MacLaine]] as Doris Mann\n* [[Dennis Quaid]] as Jack Faulkner\n* [[Gene Hackman]] as Lowell Kolchek\n* [[Richard Dreyfuss]] as Dr. Frankenthal\n* [[Rob Reiner]] as Joe Pierce\n* [[Mary Wickes]] as Grandma\n* [[Conrad Bain]] as Grandpa\n* [[Annette Bening]] as Evelyn Ames\n* [[Simon Callow]] as Simon Asquith\n* [[Gary Morton]] as Marty Wiener\n* [[C. C. H. Pounder]] as Julie Marsden\n* [[Robin Bartlett]] as Aretha\n* [[Barbara Garrick]] as Carol\n* [[Anthony Heald]] as George Lazan\n* [[Dana Ivey]] as Wardrobe Mistress\n* [[Oliver Platt]] as Neil Bleene\n* [[Robin Bartlett]] as Aretha (roommate)\n* [[Michael Ontkean]] as Robert Munch\n{{colend}}\n\nFisher said in the DVD commentary that [[Jerry Orbach]] filmed a scene as Suzanne's father, which was later cut.\n\n==Production==\nIn discussing adapting the book for the screen director Mike Nichols commented \"For quite a long time we pushed pieces around, but then we went with the central story of a mother passing the baton to her daughter.\"<ref name=EW>{{cite news|last=Dougherty |first=Margot |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318238,00.html |title='&#39;Entertainment Weekly'&#39;, September 28, 1990 |publisher=Ew.com |date=1990-09-28 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref> He added \"Carrie doesn't draw on her life any more than [[Gustave Flaubert|Flaubert]] did. It's just that his life wasn't so well known.\"<ref name=\"EW\" />\n\nNichols began pre-production in New York, where he assembled a group of actors to run lines from the script in order to perfect it. In return the actors, one of whom was [[Annette Bening]], were given small roles in the movie when it filmed.<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d_KvxiOEYGw| title=BFI Screen Talk: Annette Bening BFI London Film Festival 2017| author=BFI| publisher=YouTube.com| date=2017-11-10| access-date=2018-05-27}}</ref>\n\nResponding to questions about how closely the film's Suzanne/Doris relationship parallels her relationship with her mother, [[Debbie Reynolds]], [[Carrie Fisher]] stated \"I wrote about a mother actress and a daughter actress. I'm not shocked that people think it's about me and my mother. It's easier for them to think I have no imagination for language, just a tape recorder with endless batteries.\"<ref name=\"EW\" /> In the DVD commentary she notes that her mother wanted to portray Doris but Nichols cast [[Shirley MacLaine]] instead. In her 2013 autobiography, ''Unsinkable'', Reynolds noted that Nichols told her, \"You're not right for the part.\"\n\n[[Blue Rodeo]] accompanied [[Meryl Streep]] on \"I'm Checkin' Out,\" written by [[Shel Silverstein]]. Other songs performed in the film include \"[[I'm Still Here (Follies song)|I'm Still Here]]\" (sung by MacLaine) and \"[[You Don't Know Me (Eddy Arnold song)|You Don't Know Me]]\" (sung by Streep).\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe film earned positive reviews from critics and currently holds an 84% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 31 reviews.\n\n[[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said the film \"seems to have been a terrifically genial collaboration between the writer and the director, Miss Fisher's tale of odd-ball woe being perfect material for Mr. Nichols's particular ability to discover the humane sensibility within the absurd.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Canby |first=Vincent |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CEFD8173FF931A2575AC0A966958260 |title='&#39;New York Times'&#39; review |publisher=Movies.nytimes.com |date=1990-09-12 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' observed, \"What's disappointing about the movie is that it never really delivers on the subject of recovery from addiction. There are some incomplete, dimly seen, unrealized scenes in the rehab center, and then desultory talk about offscreen [[Alcoholics Anonymous|AA]] meetings. But the film is preoccupied with [[gossip]]; we're encouraged to wonder how many parallels there are between the Streep and MacLaine characters and their originals, Fisher and Debbie Reynolds... ''Postcards from the Edge'' contains too much good writing and too many good performances to be a failure, but its heart is not in the right place.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19900912/REVIEWS/9120301/1023 |title='&#39;Chicago Sun-Times'&#39; review |publisher=Rogerebert.suntimes.com |date= 1990-09-12|accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\nHal Hinson of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said, \"Meryl Streep gives the most fully articulated comic performance of her career, the one she's always hinted at and made us hope for.\" He felt the film's earlier section was \"the movie's best, primarily because Nichols is so focused on Streep. In fact, almost nothing else seems to matter to him... But while Nichols is servicing his star, he lets the other areas of the film go slack... [He] is finely attuned to the natural surreality of a movie set, but when he moves away from the show-biz satire and concentrates on the mother-daughter relationship, the movie falters.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/postcardsfromtheedgerhinson_a0a998.htm |title='&#39;Washington Post'&#39; review |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=1990-09-14 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\nThe film opened in 1,013 theaters in the United States on September 14, 1990 and grossed $7,871,856 on its opening weekend, ranking #1 at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|title= Postcards Takes No. 1 at Box Office Movies: Mother-daughter comedy sales hit $8.1 million. Paramount's `Ghost' is in second place on $5.8 million in sales.|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1990-09-17|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-09-17/entertainment/ca-740_1_ticket-sales|accessdate=2011-01-01|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref> It eventually earned $39,071,603 in the US.<ref name=Mojo>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=postcardsfromtheedge.htm |title=BoxOfficeMojo.com |publisher=BoxOfficeMojo.com |date=1990-11-06 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] (Meryl Streep, nominee)\n* [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] (Shel Silverstein, nominee)\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role]] (Shirley MacLaine, nominee)\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] (Carrie Fisher, nominee)\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]] (Carly Simon, nominee)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] (Meryl Streep, nominee)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture]] (Shirley MacLaine, nominee)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] (Shel Silverstein, nominee)\n* [[American Comedy Awards|American Comedy Award]] for Funniest Lead Actress in a Motion Picture (Meryl Streep, '''winner''')\n* [[London Film Critics' Circle]] Award for Newcomer of the Year (Annette Bening, '''winner''')\n[[American Film Institute]] recognition:\n* [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Laughs]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>[http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs Nominees]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0100395|Postcards from the Edge}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|postcards_from_the_edge|Postcards from the Edge}}\n* [http://www.sonypicturesmuseum.com/collection/719/postcards-from-the-edge ''Postcards From the Edge''] at the [[Sony Pictures]] Entertainment Museum\n\n{{Mike Nichols}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Postcards From The Edge}}\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mike Nichols]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Carrie Fisher]]\n[[Category:Films \u00e0 clef]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1990 film by Mike Nichols}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Postcards from the Edge\n| image = Postcards_from_the_edge.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Mike Nichols]]\n| producer = [[John Calley]]<br />Mike Nichols\n| screenplay = [[Carrie Fisher]]\n| based on = {{based on|''[[Postcards from the Edge]]''|Carrie Fisher}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Meryl Streep]]\n* [[Shirley MacLaine]]\n* [[Dennis Quaid]]}}\n| music = [[Carly Simon]]\n| editing = [[Sam O'Steen]]\n| cinematography = [[Michael Ballhaus]]\n| studio = Columbia Pictures \n| distributor = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|1990|9|14}}\n| runtime = 101 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $22 million<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/07/movies/it-s-fade-out-for-the-cheap-film-as-hollywood-s-budgets-soar.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm | work=The New York Times | first=Aljean | last=Harmetz | title=It's Fade-Out for the Cheap Film As Hollywood's Budgets Soar | date=1989-12-07}}</ref>\n| gross = $39,071,603 (US)<ref name=\"Mojo\" />\n}}\n'''''Postcards from the Edge''''' is a 1990 American [[comedy-drama|comedy-drama film]] directed by [[Mike Nichols]]. The screenplay by [[Carrie Fisher]] is based on her 1987 semi-[[Autobiography|autobiographical]] [[Postcards from the Edge|novel of the same title]]. The film stars [[Meryl Streep]], [[Shirley MacLaine]], and [[Dennis Quaid]].\n\n==Plot==\nActress Suzanne Vale ([[Meryl Streep]]) is a recovering [[Addiction|drug addict]] trying to pick up the pieces of her acting [[career]] and get on with her life after being discharged from a [[drug rehabilitation|rehab center]] to kick a [[cocaine]]-[[Oxycodone/aspirin|Percodan]] habit; after overdosing while on a date, her mother admitted her to the rehab center from the emergency room. When she is ready to return to work her agent advises her the studio's insurance policy will cover her only if she lives with a \"responsible\" individual such as her mother Doris Mann ([[Shirley MacLaine]]). Suzanne is very reluctant to return to the woman from whom she struggled to escape for years after growing up in her shadow. The situation is not helped by the fact that Doris is very loud, competitive, manipulative, self-absorbed and given to offering her daughter unsolicited advice with insinuating value judgments while treating her like a child.\n\nProducer Jack Faulkner ([[Dennis Quaid]]) runs into Suzanne on the set and reveals that he is the one who drove her to the hospital during her last overdose, and the two kiss. Suzanne then agrees to go out with him. During the course of a passionate first date, he professes intense and eternal love for her and she believes every word is true. Suzanne's euphoria is short-lived, however; she subsequently learns from Evelyn Ames ([[Annette Bening]]), a [[Bit part|bit player]] in her latest film, that Jack is sleeping with Evelyn as well. Still dressed in the costume she wears as a uniformed cop in the [[Kitsch|schlock]] movie, Suzanne drives to Jack's house and confronts him. As their argument escalates, Jack implies that Suzanne was much more interesting when she was trying to function while [[Driving under the influence|under the influence]].\n\nAt home, Suzanne learns from Doris that Suzanne's sleazy business manager Marty Wiener has absconded with all her money. This leads to a verbal brawl between the two women, and Suzanne storms out to go to a [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|looping]] session. There the paternalistic director Lowell Kolchek ([[Gene Hackman]]) tells her he has more work for her as long as she can remain clean and sober.\n\nSuzanne arrives home and discovers that Doris has crashed her car into a tree after drinking too much wine (and [[Stolichnaya]] [[smoothie]]s). Suzanne rushes to her hospital bedside where the two have a heart-to-heart talk while Suzanne fixes her mother's makeup and arranges a scarf on her head to conceal the fact she bloodied her wig in the accident. Looking and feeling better, Doris musters her courage and faces the media waiting for her. Suzanne runs into Dr. Frankenthal ([[Richard Dreyfuss]]), who had pumped her stomach after her last overdose, and he invites her to see a movie with him. She declines, telling him she's not ready to date yet. Dr. Frankenthal tells her he's willing to wait until she is.\n\nIn the film's closing moments Suzanne performs \"I'm Checkin' Out,\" a foot-stomping [[Country music|Country Western]] number, for a scene in Lowell Kolchek's new film.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Suzanne Vale\n* [[Shirley MacLaine]] as Doris Mann\n* [[Dennis Quaid]] as Jack Faulkner\n* [[Gene Hackman]] as Lowell Kolchek\n* [[Richard Dreyfuss]] as Dr. Frankenthal\n* [[Rob Reiner]] as Joe Pierce\n* [[Mary Wickes]] as Grandma\n* [[Conrad Bain]] as Grandpa\n* [[Annette Bening]] as Evelyn Ames\n* [[Simon Callow]] as Simon Asquith\n* [[Gary Morton]] as Marty Wiener\n* [[C. C. H. Pounder]] as Julie Marsden\n* [[Robin Bartlett]] as Aretha\n* [[Barbara Garrick]] as Carol\n* [[Anthony Heald]] as George Lazan\n* [[Dana Ivey]] as Wardrobe Mistress\n* [[Oliver Platt]] as Neil Bleene\n* [[Robin Bartlett]] as Aretha (roommate)\n* [[Michael Ontkean]] as Robert Munch\n{{colend}}\n\nFisher said in the DVD commentary that [[Jerry Orbach]] filmed a scene as Suzanne's father, which was later cut.\n\n==Production==\nIn discussing adapting the book for the screen director Mike Nichols commented \"For quite a long time we pushed pieces around, but then we went with the central story of a mother passing the baton to her daughter.\"<ref name=EW>{{cite news|last=Dougherty |first=Margot |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318238,00.html |title='&#39;Entertainment Weekly'&#39;, September 28, 1990 |publisher=Ew.com |date=1990-09-28 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref> He added \"Carrie doesn't draw on her life any more than [[Gustave Flaubert|Flaubert]] did. It's just that his life wasn't so well known.\"<ref name=\"EW\" />\n\nNichols began pre-production in New York, where he assembled a group of actors to run lines from the script in order to perfect it. In return the actors, one of whom was [[Annette Bening]], were given small roles in the movie when it filmed.<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d_KvxiOEYGw| title=BFI Screen Talk: Annette Bening BFI London Film Festival 2017| author=BFI| publisher=YouTube.com| date=2017-11-10| access-date=2018-05-27}}</ref>\n\nResponding to questions about how closely the film's Suzanne/Doris relationship parallels her relationship with her mother, [[Debbie Reynolds]], [[Carrie Fisher]] stated \"I wrote about a mother actress and a daughter actress. I'm not shocked that people think it's about me and my mother. It's easier for them to think I have no imagination for language, just a tape recorder with endless batteries.\"<ref name=\"EW\" /> In the DVD commentary she notes that her mother wanted to portray Doris but Nichols cast [[Shirley MacLaine]] instead. In her 2013 autobiography, ''Unsinkable'', Reynolds noted that Nichols told her, \"You're not right for the part.\"\n\n[[Blue Rodeo]] accompanied [[Meryl Streep]] on \"I'm Checkin' Out,\" written by [[Shel Silverstein]]. Other songs performed in the film include \"[[I'm Still Here (Follies song)|I'm Still Here]]\" (sung by MacLaine) and \"[[You Don't Know Me (Eddy Arnold song)|You Don't Know Me]]\" (sung by Streep).\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe film earned positive reviews from critics and currently holds an 84% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 31 reviews.\n\n[[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said the film \"seems to have been a terrifically genial collaboration between the writer and the director, Miss Fisher's tale of odd-ball woe being perfect material for Mr. Nichols's particular ability to discover the humane sensibility within the absurd.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Canby |first=Vincent |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CEFD8173FF931A2575AC0A966958260 |title='&#39;New York Times'&#39; review |publisher=Movies.nytimes.com |date=1990-09-12 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' observed, \"What's disappointing about the movie is that it never really delivers on the subject of recovery from addiction. There are some incomplete, dimly seen, unrealized scenes in the rehab center, and then desultory talk about offscreen [[Alcoholics Anonymous|AA]] meetings. But the film is preoccupied with [[gossip]]; we're encouraged to wonder how many parallels there are between the Streep and MacLaine characters and their originals, Fisher and Debbie Reynolds... ''Postcards from the Edge'' contains too much good writing and too many good performances to be a failure, but its heart is not in the right place.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19900912/REVIEWS/9120301/1023 |title='&#39;Chicago Sun-Times'&#39; review |publisher=Rogerebert.suntimes.com |date= 1990-09-12|accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\nHal Hinson of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said, \"Meryl Streep gives the most fully articulated comic performance of her career, the one she's always hinted at and made us hope for.\" He felt the film's earlier section was \"the movie's best, primarily because Nichols is so focused on Streep. In fact, almost nothing else seems to matter to him... But while Nichols is servicing his star, he lets the other areas of the film go slack... [He] is finely attuned to the natural surreality of a movie set, but when he moves away from the show-biz satire and concentrates on the mother-daughter relationship, the movie falters.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/postcardsfromtheedgerhinson_a0a998.htm |title='&#39;Washington Post'&#39; review |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=1990-09-14 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\nThe film opened in 1,013 theaters in the United States on September 14, 1990 and grossed $7,871,856 on its opening weekend, ranking #1 at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|title= Postcards Takes No. 1 at Box Office Movies: Mother-daughter comedy sales hit $8.1 million. Paramount's `Ghost' is in second place on $5.8 million in sales.|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1990-09-17|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1990-09-17/entertainment/ca-740_1_ticket-sales|accessdate=2011-01-01|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref> It eventually earned $39,071,603 in the US.<ref name=Mojo>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=postcardsfromtheedge.htm |title=BoxOfficeMojo.com |publisher=BoxOfficeMojo.com |date=1990-11-06 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] (Meryl Streep, nominee)\n* [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] (Shel Silverstein, nominee)\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role]] (Shirley MacLaine, nominee)\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] (Carrie Fisher, nominee)\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]] (Carly Simon, nominee)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] (Meryl Streep, nominee)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture]] (Shirley MacLaine, nominee)\n* [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] (Shel Silverstein, nominee)\n* [[American Comedy Awards|American Comedy Award]] for Funniest Lead Actress in a Motion Picture (Meryl Streep, '''winner''')\n* [[London Film Critics' Circle]] Award for Newcomer of the Year (Annette Bening, '''winner''')\n[[American Film Institute]] recognition:\n* [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Laughs]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>[http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs Nominees]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0100395|Postcards from the Edge}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|postcards_from_the_edge|Postcards from the Edge}}\n* [http://www.sonypicturesmuseum.com/collection/719/postcards-from-the-edge ''Postcards From the Edge''] at the [[Sony Pictures]] Entertainment Museum\n\n{{Mike Nichols}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Postcards From The Edge}}\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Mike Nichols]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Carrie Fisher]]\n[[Category:Films \u00e0 clef]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postcards_from_the_Edge_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Ayesha Takia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ayesha Takia\n| image              = Ayesha-Takia-Azmi-snapped-on-location-for-a-photoshoot-at-Aarey-Colony-.jpg\n| caption            = Takia in 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1986|04|10}}<ref>\n[https://youtube/tP9i3XRsAw4]\n[https://businessofcinema.com/bollywood_news/taarzan-girl-ayesha-takia-celebrates-birthday-today/139722 Taarzan Girl Ayesha Takia Celebrates Her Birthday Today!]. businessofcinema.com (10 April 2014) Retrieved 17 September 2015</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]] <br/> (Present day: [[Mumbai]]), <br/> [[Maharashtra]], <br/> [[India]]\n| occupation         = [[Actress]], [[voice actress]], [[Model (person)|model]], [[television presenter]]\n| years_active       = 2004\u20132011\n| spouse             = \n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Ayesha Takia''' (born 10 April 1986) is an Indian film actress who appeared in [[Bollywood]] films. She made her film debut in ''[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]'' for which she won the [[Filmfare Best Female Debut Award|Filmfare Best Debut Award]] in 2004. Her notable films also include ''[[Socha Na Tha]]'' (2005), ''[[Dor (film)|Dor]]'' (2006), for which she won the [[Screen Award for Best Actress (Critics)]], and ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' (2009).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090924094244/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=1146&nCat=news Wanted Creates History On Eid]. Box Office India. 22 September 2009</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAyesha Takia was born in Bombay, Maharashtra, India to a [[Gujarati people|Hindu]] father and [[Islam in India|Muslim]] mother, having the ethnicity of Gujarati.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Darshan|first1=Khullar|title=Pakistan: Our Difficult Neighbour and India's Islamic Dimensions|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3QmqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106|accessdate=25 January 2018|date=25 February 2014|publisher=Vij Books India Pvt Ltd, 30 September 2014|isbn=9789382652823|pages=106|chapter=Part II: Hindu Husbands and Muslim Wives}}</ref> She is an alumnus of St Anthony's Girls High School, [[Chembur]].<ref>{{cite web |url = https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Small-talk-with-Ayesha-Takia-Green-Dame/articleshow/52276788.cms |title = Small talk with Ayesha Takia - Green Dame |last = Guhal |first = Kunal |date = 28 January 2017 |accessdate = 25 January 2018 |work = [[The Times of India]] }}</ref> She married restaurateur Farhan Azmi, son of Samajwadi Party leader [[Abu Azmi]], on March 1, 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/ayesha-takia-farhan-azmi-1208800-2018-04-10|title=When Ayesha Takia was called insane for marrying Farhan Azmi at 23|newspaper=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19|agency=Ist}}</ref> She has a son with her husband Farhan Azmi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayesha Takia delivers a baby boy named Michael Azmi |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-delivers-a-baby-boy/article1-1160703.aspx|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caravanalive.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-s-son-is-the-cutest-thing-you-ll-see-today-17567.html|title=Ayesha Takia's son is the cutest thing you'll see today|last=Press|first=Alive Caravan, Delhi|work=The Caravan|access-date=21 April 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414192822/http://www.caravanalive.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-s-son-is-the-cutest-thing-you-ll-see-today-17567.html|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTakia began her career as a model when she was 15, appearing in the \"I am a Complan Boy! I\u2019m a Complan Girl!\" campaign<ref>{{cite web|title=Taarzan Girl Ayesha Takia Celebrates Her Birthday Today|url=http://businessofcinema.com/bollywood_news/taarzan-girl-ayesha-takia-celebrates-birthday-today/139722|website=businessofcinema.com|publisher=Business of Cinema|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> and also in [[Falguni Pathak]]'s \"Meri Chunar Udd Udd Jaye\" music video.<ref>{{cite web|last1=FalguniPathakVEVO|title=Falguni Pathak \u2013 Meri Chunar Udd Udd Jaye|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p9r2GxMlRD4|website=youtube.com|publisher=Universal Music India Pvt. Ltd|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> Later she appeared in the music video ''Shake It Daddy'' Remix of song Nahin Nahin Abhi Nahin along with actor [[Keith Sequeira]], both the songs were directed by [[Vinay Sapru]] and [[Radhika Rao]]. Which brought her to the attention of Bollywood, and a few film offers followed. She signed a contract to appear in ''[[Socha Na Tha]]'', then for ''[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]''. However, delays making ''[[Socha Na Tha]]'' meant that ''Taarzan'' was released first and was therefore her \"debut\" film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krishnan|first1=Aishwarya|title=Top 5 Ayesha Takia movies on her 28th birthday|url=http://www.india.com/top-n/top-5-ayesha-takia-movies-on-her-28th-birthday-37563/|publisher=Times Internet|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> She won the [[Filmfare Best Debut Award]] in 2004 for her performance in the film.\n[[File:Ayesha Takia Aug-8th-2006.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|247x247px|Ayesha at an event]]\nTakia has appeared in a number of films that did poorly at the box office. However, she has been highly praised for her work in the 2006 ''[[Dor (film)|Dor]]'', a smaller budget film in which she plays the role of a young widowed Rajasthani woman living in a traditional joint family. She went on to win several awards for her performance in the film, including the [[Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Actor \u2013 Female|Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Actress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212011415/http://sifymax.com/zca/winners/|title=Zee Cine Awards 2007, Zee TV's Bollywood awards: Vote online on Sify Max|date=2008-02-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nApart from Bollywood, Takia has also appeared in the 2005 Telugu film ''[[Super (2005 film)|Super]]'', with [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Tollywood]] star [[Akkineni Nagarjuna]], for which she was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Telugu]]. Her most recent hit was [[Prabhu Deva]]'s ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'', co-starring [[Salman Khan]], which emerged as one of the biggest blockbusters of 2009. The film was the third-highest-grossing movie of the year and her role met with positive reviews.\n\nIn 2011, she starred in ''Mod'', which met with a good response.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krishnan|first1=Aishwarya|title=Top 5 Ayesha Takia movies on her 28th birthday|url=http://www.india.com/top-n/top-5-ayesha-takia-movies-on-her-28th-birthday-37563/|publisher=Times Internet|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> In 2012, she hosted the only season of musical-reality show ''[[Sur Kshetra]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-tv-sur-kshetra/20120910.htm|title=More jingoism, less singing in Sur Kshetra|website=Rediff|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nShe is very active on social media, especially Twitter and has been a supporter for wildlife protection.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-new-look-invites-a-swarm-of-twitter-trolls-here-s-are-some-mean-tweets/story-hyi6Cz7Jo95xGR4gxGyG6H.html|title=Ayesha Takia's new look invites a swarm of Twitter trolls. Here are some mean tweets|date=25 February 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.india.com/buzz/ayesha-takia-is-the-queen-of-snapchat-filters-hot-actress-pictures-will-make-you-forget-about-redundant-lip-breast-surgery-talks-2013222/|title=Ayesha Takia is the Queen of Snapchat filters! Hot Actress' pictures will make you forget about redundant lip & breast surgery talks!|last=Mishra|first=Rashmi|date=10 April 2017|work=Times Internet|access-date=21 April 2017}}</ref> In April 2014, Ayesha denounced her father-in-law, the [[Samajwadi Party]] legislator [[Abu Azmi]], for saying that rape victims should also be punished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Ayeshatakia/statuses/454538129546833920|title=if wot im reading about my father in laws statements r true then me and Farhan are deeply embarrassed n ashamed...|last=Azmi\u2661|first=Ayesha Takia|date=2014-04-11|website=@Ayeshatakia|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/deeply-embarassed-and-ashamed-ayesha-takia-reacts-to-father-in-law-abu-azmis-rape-comment-680472.html|title=Deeply embarrassed and ashamed: Ayesha Takia reacts to father-in-law Abu Azmi's rape comment|website=News18|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> In a public statement, she has claimed to be a [[vegan]] while posing for a vegan ad for [[PETA]] India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ayesha-takia-poses-with-chick-for-peta-ahead-of-vegan-day/1/398206.html |title=Ayesha Takia Poses with CHick for PETA Ahead of Vegan Day |publisher=[[India Today]] |accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Films\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]''\n| Priya Rakesh Kapoor\n| [[Filmfare Best Female Debut Award]]{{cn|date=December 2019}}<br /> [[IIFA Award for Star Debut of the Year \u2013 Female]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> Star's Sabsey Favourite Nayi Heroine{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> Nominated\u2014[[Screen Award for Most Promising Newcomer \u2013 Female]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> Nominated\u2014[[Zee Cine Award for Best Female Debut]]{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Dil Maange More]]''\n| Shagun\n| \n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Socha Na Tha]]''\n| Aditi Sahani\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Shaadi No. 1]]''\n| Bhavna\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Super (2005 film)|Super]]''\n| Siri Valli\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]] debut\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Home Delivery (film)|Home Delivery]]''\n| Jenny\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Shaadi Se Pehle]]''\n| Rani Bhalla\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Yun Hota Toh Kya Hota]]''\n| Khushboo\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Dor (film)|Dor]]''\n| Meera\n| [[Screen Award for Best Actress (Critics)]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> [[Zee Cine Award \u2013 Critics' Choice Best Actress]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> [[Bengal Film Journalists' Association - Best Actress Award]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> [[Stardust Best Supporting Actress Award]]{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Salaam-E-Ishq]]''\n| Gia Bakshi\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Kya Love Story Hai]]''\n| Kajal Mehra\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Fool and Final]]''\n| Tina\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Cash (2007 film)|Cash]]''\n| Preeti / Riya\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Blood Brothers (short film)|Blood Brothers]]''\n| Keya\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]''\n| Anjali / Annie\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Sunday (Indian film)|Sunday]]''\n| Sehar Thapar\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[De Taali]]''\n| Amrita \"Amu\"\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[8 x 10 Tasveer]]''\n| Sheela Patel\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]''\n| Jhanvi\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Paathshala]]''\n| Anjali Mathur\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Mod (film)|Mod]]''\n| Aranya Mahadeo\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Bollywood|Biography}}\n* [[List of Indian film actresses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ayesha Takia}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=1779702}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Ayesha Takia\n| list =\n{{FilmfareAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n{{IIFAAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n{{ZeeCineAwardBestActorFemale}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takia, Ayesha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Female models from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ayesha Takia\n| image              = Ayesha-Takia-Azmi-snapped-on-location-for-a-photoshoot-at-Aarey-Colony-.jpg\n| caption            = Takia in 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|04|10}}<ref>\n[https://youtube/tP9i3XRsAw4]\n[https://businessofcinema.com/bollywood_news/taarzan-girl-ayesha-takia-celebrates-birthday-today/139722 Taarzan Girl Ayesha Takia Celebrates Her Birthday Today!]. businessofcinema.com (10 April 2014) Retrieved 17 September 2015</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]] <br/> (Present day: [[Mumbai]]), <br/> [[Maharashtra]], <br/> [[India]]\n| occupation         = [[Actress]], [[voice actress]], [[Model (person)|model]], [[television presenter]]\n| years_active       = 2004\u20132011\n| spouse             = \n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Ayesha Takia''' (born 10 April 1985) is an Indian film actress who appeared in [[Bollywood]] films. She made her film debut in ''[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]'' for which she won the [[Filmfare Best Female Debut Award|Filmfare Best Debut Award]] in 2004. Her notable films also include ''[[Socha Na Tha]]'' (2005), ''[[Dor (film)|Dor]]'' (2006), for which she won the [[Screen Award for Best Actress (Critics)]], and ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' (2009).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090924094244/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/npages.php?page=shownews&articleid=1146&nCat=news Wanted Creates History On Eid]. Box Office India. 22 September 2009</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAyesha Takia was born in Bombay, Maharashtra, India to a [[Gujarati people|Hindu]] father and [[Islam in India|Muslim]] mother, having the ethnicity of Gujarati.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Darshan|first1=Khullar|title=Pakistan: Our Difficult Neighbour and India's Islamic Dimensions|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3QmqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA106|accessdate=25 January 2018|date=25 February 2014|publisher=Vij Books India Pvt Ltd, 30 September 2014|isbn=9789382652823|pages=106|chapter=Part II: Hindu Husbands and Muslim Wives}}</ref> She is an alumnus of St Anthony's Girls High School, [[Chembur]].<ref>{{cite web |url = https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Small-talk-with-Ayesha-Takia-Green-Dame/articleshow/52276788.cms |title = Small talk with Ayesha Takia - Green Dame |last = Guhal |first = Kunal |date = 28 January 2017 |accessdate = 25 January 2018 |work = [[The Times of India]] }}</ref> She married restaurateur Farhan Azmi, son of Samajwadi Party leader [[Abu Azmi]], on March 1, 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/ayesha-takia-farhan-azmi-1208800-2018-04-10|title=When Ayesha Takia was called insane for marrying Farhan Azmi at 23|newspaper=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19|agency=Ist}}</ref> She has a son with her husband Farhan Azmi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayesha Takia delivers a baby boy named Michael Azmi |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-delivers-a-baby-boy/article1-1160703.aspx|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caravanalive.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-s-son-is-the-cutest-thing-you-ll-see-today-17567.html|title=Ayesha Takia's son is the cutest thing you'll see today|last=Press|first=Alive Caravan, Delhi|work=The Caravan|access-date=21 April 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414192822/http://www.caravanalive.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-s-son-is-the-cutest-thing-you-ll-see-today-17567.html|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTakia began her career as a model when she was 15, appearing in the \"I am a Complan Boy! I\u2019m a Complan Girl!\" campaign<ref>{{cite web|title=Taarzan Girl Ayesha Takia Celebrates Her Birthday Today|url=http://businessofcinema.com/bollywood_news/taarzan-girl-ayesha-takia-celebrates-birthday-today/139722|website=businessofcinema.com|publisher=Business of Cinema|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> and also in [[Falguni Pathak]]'s \"Meri Chunar Udd Udd Jaye\" music video.<ref>{{cite web|last1=FalguniPathakVEVO|title=Falguni Pathak \u2013 Meri Chunar Udd Udd Jaye|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p9r2GxMlRD4|website=youtube.com|publisher=Universal Music India Pvt. Ltd|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> Later she appeared in the music video ''Shake It Daddy'' Remix of song Nahin Nahin Abhi Nahin along with actor [[Keith Sequeira]], both the songs were directed by [[Vinay Sapru]] and [[Radhika Rao]]. Which brought her to the attention of Bollywood, and a few film offers followed. She signed a contract to appear in ''[[Socha Na Tha]]'', then for ''[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]''. However, delays making ''[[Socha Na Tha]]'' meant that ''Taarzan'' was released first and was therefore her \"debut\" film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krishnan|first1=Aishwarya|title=Top 5 Ayesha Takia movies on her 28th birthday|url=http://www.india.com/top-n/top-5-ayesha-takia-movies-on-her-28th-birthday-37563/|publisher=Times Internet|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> She won the [[Filmfare Best Debut Award]] in 2004 for her performance in the film.\n[[File:Ayesha Takia Aug-8th-2006.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|247x247px|Ayesha at an event]]\nTakia has appeared in a number of films that did poorly at the box office. However, she has been highly praised for her work in the 2006 ''[[Dor (film)|Dor]]'', a smaller budget film in which she plays the role of a young widowed Rajasthani woman living in a traditional joint family. She went on to win several awards for her performance in the film, including the [[Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Actor \u2013 Female|Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Actress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212011415/http://sifymax.com/zca/winners/|title=Zee Cine Awards 2007, Zee TV's Bollywood awards: Vote online on Sify Max|date=2008-02-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nApart from Bollywood, Takia has also appeared in the 2005 Telugu film ''[[Super (2005 film)|Super]]'', with [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Tollywood]] star [[Akkineni Nagarjuna]], for which she was nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Telugu]]. Her most recent hit was [[Prabhu Deva]]'s ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'', co-starring [[Salman Khan]], which emerged as one of the biggest blockbusters of 2009. The film was the third-highest-grossing movie of the year and her role met with positive reviews.\n\nIn 2011, she starred in ''Mod'', which met with a good response.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krishnan|first1=Aishwarya|title=Top 5 Ayesha Takia movies on her 28th birthday|url=http://www.india.com/top-n/top-5-ayesha-takia-movies-on-her-28th-birthday-37563/|publisher=Times Internet|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> In 2012, she hosted the only season of musical-reality show ''[[Sur Kshetra]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-tv-sur-kshetra/20120910.htm|title=More jingoism, less singing in Sur Kshetra|website=Rediff|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nShe is very active on social media, especially Twitter and has been a supporter for wildlife protection.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ayesha-takia-new-look-invites-a-swarm-of-twitter-trolls-here-s-are-some-mean-tweets/story-hyi6Cz7Jo95xGR4gxGyG6H.html|title=Ayesha Takia's new look invites a swarm of Twitter trolls. Here are some mean tweets|date=25 February 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.india.com/buzz/ayesha-takia-is-the-queen-of-snapchat-filters-hot-actress-pictures-will-make-you-forget-about-redundant-lip-breast-surgery-talks-2013222/|title=Ayesha Takia is the Queen of Snapchat filters! Hot Actress' pictures will make you forget about redundant lip & breast surgery talks!|last=Mishra|first=Rashmi|date=10 April 2017|work=Times Internet|access-date=21 April 2017}}</ref> In April 2014, Ayesha denounced her father-in-law, the [[Samajwadi Party]] legislator [[Abu Azmi]], for saying that rape victims should also be punished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Ayeshatakia/statuses/454538129546833920|title=if wot im reading about my father in laws statements r true then me and Farhan are deeply embarrassed n ashamed...|last=Azmi\u2661|first=Ayesha Takia|date=2014-04-11|website=@Ayeshatakia|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/deeply-embarassed-and-ashamed-ayesha-takia-reacts-to-father-in-law-abu-azmis-rape-comment-680472.html|title=Deeply embarrassed and ashamed: Ayesha Takia reacts to father-in-law Abu Azmi's rape comment|website=News18|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> In a public statement, she has claimed to be a [[vegan]] while posing for a vegan ad for [[PETA]] India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ayesha-takia-poses-with-chick-for-peta-ahead-of-vegan-day/1/398206.html |title=Ayesha Takia Poses with CHick for PETA Ahead of Vegan Day |publisher=[[India Today]] |accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Films\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]''\n| Priya Rakesh Kapoor\n| [[Filmfare Best Female Debut Award]]{{cn|date=December 2019}}<br /> [[IIFA Award for Star Debut of the Year \u2013 Female]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> Star's Sabsey Favourite Nayi Heroine{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> Nominated\u2014[[Screen Award for Most Promising Newcomer \u2013 Female]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> Nominated\u2014[[Zee Cine Award for Best Female Debut]]{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Dil Maange More]]''\n| Shagun\n| \n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Socha Na Tha]]''\n| Aditi Sahani\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Shaadi No. 1]]''\n| Bhavna\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Super (2005 film)|Super]]''\n| Siri Valli\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]] debut\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Home Delivery (film)|Home Delivery]]''\n| Jenny\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Shaadi Se Pehle]]''\n| Rani Bhalla\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Yun Hota Toh Kya Hota]]''\n| Khushboo\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Dor (film)|Dor]]''\n| Meera\n| [[Screen Award for Best Actress (Critics)]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> [[Zee Cine Award \u2013 Critics' Choice Best Actress]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> [[Bengal Film Journalists' Association - Best Actress Award]]{{cn|date=December 2019}} <br /> [[Stardust Best Supporting Actress Award]]{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Salaam-E-Ishq]]''\n| Gia Bakshi\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Kya Love Story Hai]]''\n| Kajal Mehra\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Fool and Final]]''\n| Tina\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Cash (2007 film)|Cash]]''\n| Preeti / Riya\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Blood Brothers (short film)|Blood Brothers]]''\n| Keya\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]''\n| Anjali / Annie\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Sunday (Indian film)|Sunday]]''\n| Sehar Thapar\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[De Taali]]''\n| Amrita \"Amu\"\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[8 x 10 Tasveer]]''\n| Sheela Patel\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]''\n| Jhanvi\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Paathshala]]''\n| Anjali Mathur\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Mod (film)|Mod]]''\n| Aranya Mahadeo\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Bollywood|Biography}}\n* [[List of Indian film actresses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ayesha Takia}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=1779702}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Ayesha Takia\n| list =\n{{FilmfareAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n{{IIFAAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n{{ZeeCineAwardBestActorFemale}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takia, Ayesha}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Female models from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n", "name_user": "142.183.234.128", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayesha_Takia"}
{"title_page": "Christopher Atkins", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people|Chris Atkins}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Christopher Atkins\n| image       = Christopher_Atkins_2009.jpg\n| caption     = Atkins attending the [[Bench Warmer International|Bench Warmer]] Holiday Party at Empire, Hollywood, California on December 5, 2009\n| birth_name  = Christopher Atkins Bomann\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|2|21|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rye, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years_active = 1977&ndash;present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Lyn Barron|1985|2007|end=div.}}\n| children    = Grant Bomann<br />Brittney Bomann\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Atkins''' (born '''Christopher Atkins Bomann''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/atkins-christopher-1961|title=Atkins, Christopher 1961\u2013 &#124; Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref> February 21, 1961)<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\">{{cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/rye/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-ryes-christopher-atkins/434296/|title=Happy Birthday To Rye's Christopher Atkins|date=February 21, 2014|website=Rye Daily Voice}}</ref> is an American actor who became famous following his debut film role in the 1980 film ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Atkins Bomann was born<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> and raised<ref name=\"people.com\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/from-the-depths-vol-54-no-15/|title=From the Depths|website=People.com|last=Tauber|first=Michelle|date=October 9, 2000}}</ref> in [[Rye, New York]]. He is the son of Donald Bomann and Bitsy Nebauer, who divorced during his childhood.<ref name=\"people.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/look-out-j-r-chris-atkins-is-muscling-in-on-the-action-as-dallas-beefs-up-its-cast-vol-20-no-2/|title=Look Out, J.R.\u2014Chris Atkins Is Muscling in on the Action as Dallas Beefs Up Its Cast|last=Wallace|first=\nDavid|website=People.com|date=July 11, 1983}}</ref> Atkins was an aspiring baseball player; when his baseball aspirations were derailed by knee problems, he started a modeling career. When he began acting, Atkins dropped the last name Bomann and used his middle name, Atkins, as his last name.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\nA friend suggested that Atkins audition for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins won the role over thousands of other actors; the film's director, Randal Kleiser, has said that Atkins was a sailing instructor with no acting experience when he was cast in the film.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In the film, he and co-star [[Brooke Shields]] played two teenaged cousins who find love while living in an isolated tropical paradise after being marooned as children.<ref name=\"Much\"/> Released in 1980, the film grossed over $58 million with a production cost of $4.5 million<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Blue-Lagoon-The#tab=summary | title=The Blue Lagoon (1980) - Financial Information |work=The-Numbers.com|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/56372|website=AFI.com|title=AFI Catalog of Feature Films: The First 100 Years 1893\u20131993|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/21857%7C0/The-Blue-Lagoon.html|title=The Blue Lagoon|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> but received a negative critical response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blue_lagoon/|title=The Blue Lagoon|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> Atkins appeared nude<ref name=\"Much\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-too-much-too-young-vol-14-no-6/|title=Too Much, Too Young?|work=People|last=McMurrin|first=Kristin|date=August 11, 1980|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/entertainment-news/2009/01/29/christopher-atkins-poster-child-gay-rights-movement|title=Christopher Atkins: Poster Child for Gay Rights Movement?|work=Advocate.com|date=January 9, 2009|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> (including frontal nudity<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodshow.com/starDetail.php?id=3|title=Chris Atkins|work=HollywoodShow.com|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>) in the film, and spent much of the film wearing a loincloth.<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> While ''Blue Lagoon'' was controversial due to its nude scenes and sexual content,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/chazs-blog/sexualized-innocence-revisiting-the-blue-lagoon|title=Sexualized Innocence: Revisiting The Blue Lagoon| first=Abbey|last=Bender|website=www.RogerEbert.com|date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> it nevertheless became a \"pop culture phenomenon\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/the-blue-lagoon-turns-35-trivia-for-brooke-shields-and-christopher-atkins-film/|title=Celebrate The Blue Lagoon's 35th Anniversary with 10 Movie Facts You Should Know|website=People.com|last=Mackie |first=Drew |date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Atkins was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for New Star of the Year in a Motion Picture \u2013 Male for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2012/03/denise-richards-blue-lagoon-remake-christopher-atkins-cameo-241315/|title=Denise Richards To Co-Star In 'Blue Lagoon' Reboot, Christopher Atkins To Make Cameo|first1=Nellie|last1=Andreeva|work=Deadline.com|date=March 8, 2012}}</ref> \n[[File:Chris Atkins 1981.jpg|thumb|left|Atkins in 1981]] \nAtkins posed nude for ''[[Playgirl]]''<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> in 1982.<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\"/> He went on to star with [[Kristy McNichol]] in ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982), an update of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]'s operetta ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> His song \"How Can I Live Without Her\", which peaked at #71 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], was played in the film.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins portrayed Rick Monroe, a college student working as an exotic dancer, in ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983);<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> he won the 1983 Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor for his performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/opinion/reliving-reckless-by-bryan-adams-1.2179670|title=Reliving Reckless by Bryan Adams|last=Fleming|first=Andrew|website=Vancouver Courier|date=November 27, 2014}}</ref> For one season (1983\u20131984), Atkins had a recurring role as camp counselor Peter Richards on ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins appeared in the television situation comedy ''Suddenly Susan'', which starred Shields, in 1999.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In 2009, Atkins appeared on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'', a reality show featuring former teen idols.<ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/01/02/christopher-atk/|title=Christopher Atkins: PopWatch 'Teen Idol' Q&A (Part 4 of 4)|website=EW.com|last=Bierly |first=Mandy| date=January 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2009/01/06/idol_hopes_underlie_these_confessions/|title=Idol hopes underlie these 'Confessions'|first=Mary|last=McNamara|date=January 6, 2009|via=The Boston Globe}}</ref> He has been ranked no. 76 on VH1's list of 100 Greatest Teen Stars.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins became a luxury pool builder.<ref name=\"ew.com\"/> He also developed the Christopher Atkins Strike Jacket E.F.L. (Extreme Fishing Lure)--\"a rubbery slipcovering for traditional baits\"--with the assistance of special-effects expert Mark Viniello.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Brittney Bomann and Christopher Atkins.JPG|right|thumb|Atkins and his daughter on the red carpet at the 62nd&nbsp;Annual Mother Goose Parade in San Diego County, 2008]]\nAtkins married Lynne Barron Weber of [[Sydney, Australia]], on 25&nbsp;May 1985. The couple have two children: Son Grant Bomann and daughter Brittney Bomann.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/actor-christopher-atkins-wife-lyn-barron-daughter-brittney-news-photo/142000266 |series=Ron Galella archive |year=2012 |title=Actor Christopher Atkins, wife Lyn Barron, daughter Brittney Bomann and son Grant Bomann |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nndb.com/people/819/000025744/ |title=Christopher Atkins |website=nndb.com |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> The couple divorced in 2007.<ref name=People200902>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/archive/christopher-atkins-second-act-vol-71-no-6/ |title=Christopher Atkins second act |magazine=People |volume=71 |issue=6 |last=Rizzo |first=Monica |date=16 February 2009 |access-date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2009 interview, Atkins acknowledged his past struggle with alcoholism and stated that he had been sober for 22&nbsp;years.<ref name=People200902/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1980) as Richard Lestrange\n* ''[[Swan Lake (1981 film)|Swan Lake]]'' (1981) (voice) as Prince Siegfried\n* ''[[Child Bride of Short Creek]]'' (1981) ([[television film|TV]]) as Isaac King\n* ''[[Aladdin and the Wonderful Lamp (1982 film)|Aladdin and the Magic Lamp]]'' (1982) (voice) as Aladdin\n* ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982) as Frederic\n* ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983) as Rick Monroe\n* ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' (1983\u201384) as Peter Richards\n* ''Secret Weapons'' (1985) as Allan Collier\n* ''El ataque de los p\u00e1jaros'', also known as ''Evil Birds'' and ''Beaks: The Movie'' (1987) as Peter\n* ''[[Mortuary Academy]]'' (1988) as Max Grimm\n* ''[[Listen to Me (film)|Listen to Me]]'' (1989) as Bruce Arlington\n* ''[[Shakma]]'' (1990) as Sam\n* ''[[Fatal Charm (1990 film)|Fatal Charm]]'' (1990) as Adam\n* ''King's Ransom'' (1991) as Spence\n* ''Extralarge: Miami Killer'' (1991) as Blake\n* ''[[Exchange Lifeguards|Wet and Wild Summer!]]'' (1992) as Bobby McCain\n* ''Dracula Rising'' (1993) as Vlad\n* ''[[Die Watching]]'' (1993) as Michael Terrence\n* ''[[\u00a1Dispara!]]'' (1993) as Spence\n* ''Trigger Fast'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Signal One]]'' (1994) as Martin Bullet\n* ''Guns of Honor'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Bandit (film series)|Bandit Goes Country]]'' (1994) as Johnny Bruce\n* ''Smoke n Lightnin'' (1995) as Lightnin'\n* ''[[Project Shadowchaser III]]'' (1995) as Snake\n* ''[[Red Shoe Diaries]]'' (1996) (segment \"Four on the Floor\")\n* ''[[It's My Party (film)|It's My Party]]'' (1996) as Jack Allen\n* ''[[Dead Man's Island]]'' (1996) (TV) as Roger Prescott\n* ''Angel Flight Down'' (1996) as Jack Bahr\n* ''[[Mutual Needs]]'' (1997) as Andrew\n* ''Shoot'' (1998) as Spence\n* ''[[Lima: Breaking the Silence]]'' (1998) as Jeff\n* ''Deadly Delusions'' (1999) as Sam Gitlin\n* ''Stageghost'' (2000) as Matthew Bronson\n* ''[[Dark Realm]]'' (2000) ([[TV Series]])\n* ''Civility'' (2000) as John Cade\n* ''[[Title to Murder]]'' (2001) as Paul Shaughnessy\n* ''[[The Little Unicorn]]'' (2001) as PC Sid Edwards\n* ''Tequila Express'' (2002) as David Manning\n* ''The Stoneman'' (2002) as Kip Hollings\n* ''[[Mending Fences]]'' (2002) as Tom\n* ''The Employee of the Month'' (2002) as Bill\n* ''The Color of Water'' (2002) as Clay\n* ''[[13th Child]]'' (2002) as Ron\n* ''[[Quigley (film)|Quigley]]'' (2003) as Woodward Channing\n* ''True Legends of the West'' (2003) as Theodore Sutherland\n* ''[[The Librarians (film)|The Librarians]]'', a.k.a. ''Strike Force'', (2004) as Ringo\n* ''[[Caved In: Prehistoric Terror]]'' (2005) as John Palmer\n* ''Spiritual Warriors'' (2005) as King of Sparta\n* ''[[100 Million BC]]'' (2007) as Erik Reno\n* ''[[Cach\u00e9 (film)|Hidden]]'' (2008) as Walter\n* ''Chinaman's Chance: America's Yellow Slaves'' (2008) as Jacob\n* ''[[Forget Me Not (2009 film)|Forget Me Not]]'' (2008) as Mr. Channing \n* ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Exodus Fall]]'' (2009) as Wayne Minor\n* ''[[Gathering of Heroes: Legend of the Seven Swords]]'' (2009) as Garrik Grayraven\n* ''The Hard Ride'' (2009) as George Custer\n* ''Prism'' (2009) as Detective Shane Dover\n* ''The Earth Empires: Ottoman Invasion'' (2010) as jannisery Commander Murat of the Dark\n* ''Harley's Hill'' (2011) as Mr. Miller\n* ''[[Blue Lagoon: The Awakening]]'' (2012) as Mr. Christiansen\n* ''Waiting in the Wings: The Musical'' (2014) as Priest\n* ''A Horse for Summer'' (2015) as Pastor Bob\n* ''Kids vs. Monsters'' (2015) as Charles\n* ''The Sparrows'' (2015) as Mike Sparrow\n* ''One Remains'' (film) (2019) as Samuel Mahoney\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|christopher.atkins.509}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|803}}\n* {{AllMovie name|2694}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atkins, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people|Chris Atkins}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Christopher Atkins\n| image       = Christopher_Atkins_2009.jpg\n| caption     = Atkins attending the [[Bench Warmer International|Bench Warmer]] Holiday Party at Empire, Hollywood, California on December 5, 2009\n| birth_name  = Christopher Atkins Bomann\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|2|21|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rye, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years_active = 1977&ndash;present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Lyn Barron|1985|2007|end=div.}}\n| children    = Grant Bomann<br />Brittney Bomann\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Atkins''' (born '''Christopher Atkins Bomann''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/atkins-christopher-1961|title=Atkins, Christopher 1961\u2013 &#124; Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref> February 21, 1961)<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\">{{cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/rye/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-ryes-christopher-atkins/434296/|title=Happy Birthday To Rye's Christopher Atkins|date=February 21, 2014|website=Rye Daily Voice}}</ref> is an American actor who became famous following his debut film role in the 1980 film ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Atkins Bomann was born<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> and raised<ref name=\"people.com\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/from-the-depths-vol-54-no-15/|title=From the Depths|website=People.com|last=Tauber|first=Michelle|date=October 9, 2000}}</ref> in [[Rye, New York]]. He is the son of Donald Bomann and Bitsy Nebauer, who divorced during his childhood.<ref name=\"people.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/look-out-j-r-chris-atkins-is-muscling-in-on-the-action-as-dallas-beefs-up-its-cast-vol-20-no-2/|title=Look Out, J.R.\u2014Chris Atkins Is Muscling in on the Action as Dallas Beefs Up Its Cast|last=Wallace|first=\nDavid|website=People.com|date=July 11, 1983}}</ref> Atkins was an aspiring baseball player; when his baseball aspirations were derailed by knee problems, he started a modeling career. When he began acting, Atkins dropped the last name Bomann and used his middle name, Atkins, as his last name.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\nA friend suggested that Atkins audition for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins won the role over thousands of other actors; the film's director, Randal Kleiser, has said that Atkins was a sailing instructor with no acting experience when he was cast in the film.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In the film, he and co-star [[Brooke Shields]] played two teenaged cousins who find love while living in an isolated tropical paradise after being marooned as children.<ref name=\"Much\"/> Released in 1980, the film grossed over $58 million with a production cost of $4.5 million<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Blue-Lagoon-The#tab=summary | title=The Blue Lagoon (1980) - Financial Information |work=The-Numbers.com|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/56372|website=AFI.com|title=AFI Catalog of Feature Films: The First 100 Years 1893\u20131993|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/21857%7C0/The-Blue-Lagoon.html|title=The Blue Lagoon|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> but received a negative critical response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blue_lagoon/|title=The Blue Lagoon|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> Atkins appeared nude<ref name=\"Much\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-too-much-too-young-vol-14-no-6/|title=Too Much, Too Young?|work=People|last=McMurrin|first=Kristin|date=August 11, 1980|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/entertainment-news/2009/01/29/christopher-atkins-poster-child-gay-rights-movement|title=Christopher Atkins: Poster Child for Gay Rights Movement?|work=Advocate.com|date=January 9, 2009|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> (including frontal nudity<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodshow.com/starDetail.php?id=3|title=Chris Atkins|work=HollywoodShow.com|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>) in the film, and spent much of the film wearing a loincloth.<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> While ''Blue Lagoon'' was controversial due to its nude scenes and sexual content,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/chazs-blog/sexualized-innocence-revisiting-the-blue-lagoon|title=Sexualized Innocence: Revisiting The Blue Lagoon| first=Abbey|last=Bender|website=www.RogerEbert.com|date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> it nevertheless became a \"pop culture phenomenon\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/the-blue-lagoon-turns-35-trivia-for-brooke-shields-and-christopher-atkins-film/|title=Celebrate The Blue Lagoon's 35th Anniversary with 10 Movie Facts You Should Know|website=People.com|last=Mackie |first=Drew |date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Atkins was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for New Star of the Year in a Motion Picture \u2013 Male for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2012/03/denise-richards-blue-lagoon-remake-christopher-atkins-cameo-241315/|title=Denise Richards To Co-Star In 'Blue Lagoon' Reboot, Christopher Atkins To Make Cameo|first1=Nellie|last1=Andreeva|work=Deadline.com|date=March 8, 2012}}</ref> \n[[File:Chris Atkins 1981.jpg|thumb|left|Atkins in 1981]] \nAtkins posed nude for ''[[Playgirl]]''<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> in 1982.<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\"/> He went on to star with [[Kristy McNichol]] in ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982), an update of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]'s operetta ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> His song \"How Can I Live Without Her\", which peaked at #71 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], was played in the film.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins portrayed Rick Monroe, a college student working as an exotic dancer, in ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983);<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> he won the 1983 Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor for his performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/opinion/reliving-reckless-by-bryan-adams-1.2179670|title=Reliving Reckless by Bryan Adams|last=Fleming|first=Andrew|website=Vancouver Courier|date=November 27, 2014}}</ref> For one season (1983\u20131984), Atkins had a recurring role as camp counselor Peter Richards on ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins appeared in the television situation comedy ''Suddenly Susan'', which starred Shields, in 1999.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In 2009, Atkins appeared on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'', a reality show featuring former teen idols.<ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/01/02/christopher-atk/|title=Christopher Atkins: PopWatch 'Teen Idol' Q&A (Part 4 of 4)|website=EW.com|last=Bierly |first=Mandy| date=January 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2009/01/06/idol_hopes_underlie_these_confessions/|title=Idol hopes underlie these 'Confessions'|first=Mary|last=McNamara|date=January 6, 2009|via=The Boston Globe}}</ref> He has been ranked no. 76 on VH1's list of 100 Greatest Teen Stars.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins became a luxury pool builder.<ref name=\"ew.com\"/> He also developed the Christopher Atkins Strike Jacket E.F.L. (Extreme Fishing Lure)--\"a rubbery slipcovering for traditional baits\"--with the assistance of special-effects expert Mark Viniello.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Brittney Bomann and Christopher Atkins.JPG|right|thumb|Atkins and his daughter on the red carpet at the 62nd&nbsp;Annual Mother Goose Parade in San Diego County, 2008]]\nAtkins married Lynne Barron Weber of [[Sydney, Australia]], on 25&nbsp;May 1985. The couple have two children: Son Grant Bomann and daughter Brittney Bomann.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/actor-christopher-atkins-wife-lyn-barron-daughter-brittney-news-photo/142000266 |series=Ron Galella archive |year=2012 |title=Actor Christopher Atkins, wife Lyn Barron, daughter Brittney Bomann and son Grant Bomann |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nndb.com/people/819/000025744/ |title=Christopher Atkins |website=nndb.com |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> The couple divorced in 2007.<ref name=People200902>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/archive/christopher-atkins-second-act-vol-71-no-6/ |title=Christopher Atkins second act |magazine=People |volume=71 |issue=6 |last=Rizzo |first=Monica |date=16 February 2009 |access-date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2009 interview, Atkins acknowledged his past struggle with alcoholism and stated that he had been sober for 22&nbsp;years.<ref name=People200902/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1980) as Richard Lestrange\n* ''[[Swan Lake (1981 film)|Swan Lake]]'' (1981) (voice) as Prince Siegfried\n* ''[[Child Bride of Short Creek]]'' (1981) ([[television film|TV]]) as Isaac King\n* ''[[Aladdin and the Wonderful Lamp (1982 film)|Aladdin and the Magic Lamp]]'' (1982) (voice) as Aladdin\n* ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982) as Frederic\n* ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983) as Rick Monroe\n* ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' (1983\u201384) as Peter Richards\n* ''Secret Weapons'' (1985) as Allan Collier\n* ''El ataque de los p\u00e1jaros'', also known as ''Evil Birds'' and ''Beaks: The Movie'' (1987) as Peter\n* ''[[Mortuary Academy]]'' (1988) as Max Grimm\n* ''[[Listen to Me (film)|Listen to Me]]'' (1989) as Bruce Arlington\n* ''[[Shakma]]'' (1990) as Sam\n* ''[[Fatal Charm (1990 film)|Fatal Charm]]'' (1990) as Adam\n* ''King's Ransom'' (1991) as Spence\n* ''Extralarge: Miami Killer'' (1991) as Blake\n* ''[[Exchange Lifeguards|Wet and Wild Summer!]]'' (1992) as Bobby McCain\n* ''Dracula Rising'' (1993) as Vlad\n* ''[[Die Watching]]'' (1993) as Michael Terrence\n* ''[[\u00a1Dispara!]]'' (1993) as Spence\n* ''Trigger Fast'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Signal One]]'' (1994) as Martin Bullet\n* ''Guns of Honor'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Bandit (film series)|Bandit Goes Country]]'' (1994) as Johnny Bruce\n* ''Smoke n