ristiansen\n* ''Waiting in the Wings: The Musical'' (2014) as Priest\n* ''A Horse for Summer'' (2015) as Pastor Bob\n* ''Kids vs. Monsters'' (2015) as Charles\n* ''The Sparrows'' (2015) as Mike Sparrow\n* ''One Remains'' (film) (2019) as Samuel Mahoney\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|christopher.atkins.509}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|803}}\n* {{AllMovie name|2694}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atkins, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Atkins"}
{"title_page": "DAMA/NaI", "text_new": "{{about|an experiment||Dama (disambiguation)}} The '''DAMA/NaI experiment'''<ref name=\"rnc\">{{cite journal\n |author=Bernabei, R. \n |display-authors=etal\n |year=2003\n |title=Dark Matter search\n |journal=[[Rivista del Nuovo Cimento]]\n |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=1\n |doi=\n |arxiv=astro-ph/0307403\n |bibcode=2003NCimR..26a...1B }}</ref><ref name=\"perf\">{{cite journal\n |author=Bernabei, R. \n |display-authors=etal\n |year=1999\n |title=Performances of the about 100&nbsp;kg NaI(Tl) set-up of the DAMA experiment at Gran Sasso\n |journal=[[Il Nuovo Cimento A]]\n |volume=112 |issue=6 |pages=545\u2013575\n |doi=10.1007/BF03035868\n |bibcode=1999NCimA.112..545B }}</ref> investigated the presence of [[Dark Matter|dark matter]] particles in the galactic halo by exploiting the model-independent annual modulation signature. Based on the Earth's orbit around the Sun and the solar system's speed with respect to the center of the galaxy (which on short time scales can be considered constant), the [[Earth]] should be exposed to a higher flux of dark matter particles around June&nbsp;2,{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} when its [[orbital speed]] is added to the one of the solar system with respect to the [[galaxy]] and to a smaller one around December&nbsp;2, when the two velocities are subtracted. The annual modulation signature is distinctive since the effect induced by dark matter particles must simultaneously satisfy many requirements.\n\n==Description==\nThe experimental set-up was located deep underground in the [[Laboratori Nazionali del Gran Sasso]] in [[Italy]].\n\nThe experimental set-up was made by nine 9.70&nbsp;kg low-radioactivity scintillating [[thallium]]-doped [[sodium iodide]]  [[crystal]]s [NaI(Tl)]. Each crystal was faced by two low-background [[photomultiplier]]s through 10&nbsp;cm light guides. The detectors were installed inside a sealed copper box flushed with highly pure nitrogen in order to insulate the detectors from air that contains trace amounts of radon, a radioactive gas. To reduce the natural environmental background the copper box is enclosed inside a multicomponent multi-ton passive shield made of copper, lead, polyethylene/paraffin, cadmium foil. A [[Poly(methyl methacrylate)|plexiglas]] box encloses the whole shield and is also kept in a highly pure nitrogen atmosphere. A concrete [[neutron]] moderator 1&nbsp;m thick largely surrounds the set-up.\n\n==Results==\nThe DAMA/NaI set-up observed the annual modulation signature over 7&nbsp;annual cycles (1995\u20132002). The presence of a model independent positive evidence in the data of DAMA/NaI was first reported by the DAMA collaboration in fall&nbsp;1997 and published beginning of 1998.<ref name=\"mod1\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=1998 |title=Searching for WIMPs by the annual modulation signature |journal=[[Physics Letters B]] |volume=424 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=195\u2013201 |doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(98)00172-5 |bibcode=1998PhLB..424..195B}}</ref> The final paper with the full results was published in 2003 after the end of experiment in July&nbsp;2002.<ref name=\"rnc\" /> Various corollary investigations are continuing and have also been published.<ref name=\"sisd\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2001 |title=Investigating the DAMA annual modulation data in a mixed coupling framework |journal=[[Physics Letters B]] |volume=509 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=197\u2013203 |doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(01)00493-2 |bibcode=2001PhLB..509..197B }}</ref><ref name=\"inel\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2002 |title=Investigating the DAMA annual modulation data in the framework of inelastic dark matter |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=61\u201364 |doi=10.1007/s100520100854 |bibcode=2002EPJC...23...61B }}</ref><ref name=\"halo\">{{cite journal |author1=Belli, P. |display-authors=etal |year=2002 |title=Effect of the galactic halo modeling on the DAMA-NaI annual modulation result: An extended analysis of the data for weakly interacting massive particles with a purely spin-independent coupling |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=66 |issue=4 |pages=043503 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.66.043503 |arxiv=hep-ph/0203242 |bibcode=2002PhRvD..66d3503B}}</ref><ref name=\"ijmpd\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2004 |title=Dark matter particles in the galactic halo: Results and implications from DAMA/NaI |journal=[[International Journal of Modern Physics D]] |volume=13 |issue=10 |pages=2127\u20132159 |doi=10.1142/S0218271804006619 |arxiv=astro-ph/0501412 |bibcode=2004IJMPD..13.2127B }}</ref><ref name=\"ijmpa\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2006 |title=Investigating pseudoscalar and scalar dark matter |journal=[[International Journal of Modern Physics A]] |volume=21 |issue=7 |pages=1445\u20131469 |doi=10.1142/S0217751X06030874 |arxiv=astro-ph/0511262 |bibcode=2006IJMPA..21.1445B }}</ref><ref name=\"sag\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2006 |title=Investigating halo substructures with annual modulation signature |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=47 |issue= 1|pages=263\u2013271 |doi=10.1140/epjc/s2006-02559-9 |arxiv=astro-ph/0604303 |bibcode=2006EPJC...47..263B }}</ref><ref name=\"migdal\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2007 |title=On electromagnetic contributions in WIMP quests  |journal=[[International Journal of Modern Physics A]] |volume=22 |issue=19 |pages=3155\u20133168 |doi=10.1142/S0217751X07037093 |arxiv=0706.1421 |bibcode= 2007IJMPA..22.3155B}}</ref><ref name=\"wimpele\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2008 |title=Investigating electron interacting dark matter  |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=3155\u20133168 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.77.023506 |arxiv=0706.1421 |bibcode=2008PhRvD..77b3506B }}</ref><ref name=\"chan\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2008 |title=Possible implications of the channeling effect in NaI(Tl) crystals |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=53 |issue=2 |pages=205\u2013213 |doi=10.1140/epjc/s10052-007-0479-0 |arxiv=0710.0288 |bibcode=2008EPJC...53..205B}}</ref><ref name=\"ldm\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2008 |title=Investigation on light dark matter |journal=[[Modern Physics Letters A]] |volume=23 |issue=26 |pages=2125\u20132140 |doi=10.1142/S0217732308027473 |arxiv=0802.4336 |bibcode=2008MPLA...23.2125B }}</ref>\n\nThe model-independent evidence is compatible with a wide set of scenarios regarding the nature of the dark matter candidate and related astrophysical, nuclear and [[Particle Physics|particle physics]],<ref name=\"foot\">{{cite journal |author=Foot, R. |year=2004 |title=Reconciling the positive DAMA annual modulation signal with the negative results of the CDMS&nbsp;II experiment |journal=[[Modern Physics Letters A]] |volume=19 |issue=24 |pages=1841\u20131846 |doi=10.1142/S0217732304015051 |arxiv=astro-ph/0405362 |bibcode=2004MPLA...19.1841F }}</ref> for example: [[Neutralino|neutralinos]],<ref name=\"bot1\">{{cite journal |author1=Bottino, A. |display-authors=etal |year=2003 |title=Light Relic Neutralinos |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=67 |issue=6 |pages=063519 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.67.063519 |arxiv=hep-ph/0212379 |bibcode=2003PhRvD..67f3519B}}</ref><ref name=\"bot2\">{{cite journal |author1=Bottino, A. |display-authors=etal |year=2003 |title=Lower bound on the neutralino mass from new data on CMB and implications for relic neutralinos |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=043506 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.68.043506 |arxiv=hep-ph/0304080  |bibcode=2003PhRvD..68d3506B}}</ref><ref name=\"bot3\">{{cite journal |author1=Bottino, A. |display-authors=etal |year=2004 |title=Light neutralinos and WIMP direct searches  |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=69 |issue=3 |pages=037302 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.69.037302 |arxiv=hep-ph/0307303 |bibcode=2004PhRvD..69c7302B}}</ref> inelastic dark matter,<ref name=\"smit\">{{cite journal |author1=Smith, D.T. |author2=Weiner, N. |year=2005 |title=The Status of Inelastic Dark Matter |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=72 |pages=063509 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.72.063509 |arxiv=hep-ph/0402065 |bibcode=2005PhRvD..72f3509T |issue=6}}</ref> [[self-interacting dark matter]],<ref name=\"mitr\">{{cite journal |author=Mitra, S.  |year=2005 |title=Has Dama Detected Self-Interacting Dark Matter? |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=71 |issue=12 |pages=121302 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.71.121302 |arxiv=astro-ph/0409121 |bibcode=2005PhRvD..71l1302M }}</ref> and heavy 4th&nbsp;generation [[Neutrino|neutrinos]],<ref name=\"belo1\">{{cite journal |author1=Belotsky, K.M. |author2=Damour, T. |author3=Khlopov, M. Yu. |year=2002 |title=Implications of a solar-system population of massive 4th&nbsp;generation neutrinos for underground searches of monochromatic neutrino-annihilation signals |journal=[[Physics Letters B]] |volume=529 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=10\u201318 |doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(02)01234-0 |arxiv=astro-ph/0201314 |bibcode=2002PhLB..529...10B}}</ref><ref name=\"belo2\">{{cite journal |author1=Belotsky, K. |author2=Fargion, D. |author3=Khlopov, M. |author4=Konoplich, R.V. |year=2008 |title=May Heavy neutrinos solve underground and cosmic ray puzzles? |journal=[[Physics of Atomic Nuclei]] |volume=71 |issue=1 |pages=147\u2013161 |doi=10.1007/s11450-008-1016-9 |arxiv=hep-ph/0411093 |bibcode=2008PAN....71..147B}}</ref>\n\nA careful quantitative investigation of possible sources of systematic and side reactions has been regularly carried out and published at the time of each data release.<ref name=\"sist\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2000 |title=On the investigation of possible systematics in WIMP annual modulation search |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=283\u2013292 |doi=10.1007/s100520000540 |bibcode=2000EPJC...18..283B}}</ref> No systematic effect or side reaction able to account for the observed modulation amplitude and to simultaneously satisfy all the requirements of the signature has been found.\n\nThe experiment has also obtained and published many results on other processes and/or approaches.\n\n==Skepticism==\nNegative results from the [[XENON Dark Matter Search Experiment]] seem to contradict DAMA/Nal's results.<ref name=sciamer>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=dama-dark-matter |title=WIMP Wars: Astronomers and physicists remain skeptical of long-standing dark matter claim |last=Matson |first=John |date=6 May 2011 |magazine=Scientific American |access-date=12 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Korea Invisible Mass Search#COSINE|COSINE-100]] collaboration has been working in Korea towards confirming or refuting the DAMA-signal. They are using similar experimental setup to DAMA (NaI(Ti)-crystals). They published their results in December 2018 in the journal Nature; their conclusion was that their \"result rules out WIMP\u2013nucleon interactions as the cause of the annual modulation observed by the DAMA collaboration\". <ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/s41586-018-0739-1|pmid = 30518890| title=An experiment to search for dark-matter interactions using sodium iodide detectors| journal=Nature| volume=564| issue=7734| pages=83\u201386| year=2018| author1=COSINE-100 Collaboration| bibcode=2018Natur.564...83C| last2=Adhikari| first2=Govinda| last3=Adhikari| first3=Pushparaj| last4=Barbosa De Souza| first4=Estella| last5=Carlin| first5=Nelson| last6=Choi| first6=Seonho| last7=Djamal| first7=Mitra| last8=Ezeribe| first8=Anthony C.| last9=Ha| first9=Chang Hyon| last10=Hahn| first10=Insik | authorlink10=Kevin Insik Hahn| last11=Hubbard| first11=Antonia J. F.| last12=Jeon| first12=Eunju| last13=Jo| first13=Jay Hyun| last14=Joo| first14=Hanwool| last15=Kang| first15=Woon Gu| last16=Kang| first16=Woosik| last17=Kauer| first17=Matthew| last18=Kim| first18=Bonghee| last19=Kim| first19=Hongjoo| last20=Kim| first20=Hyounggyu| last21=Kim| first21=Kyungwon| last22=Kim| first22=Nam Young| last23=Kim| first23=Sun Kee| last24=Kim| first24=Yeongduk| last25=Kim| first25=Yong-Hamb| last26=Ko| first26=Young Ju| last27=Kudryavtsev| first27=Vitaly Y.| last28=Lee| first28=Hyun Su| last29=Lee| first29=Jaison| last30=Lee| first30=Jooyoung| displayauthors=29|arxiv = 1906.01791}}</ref>\n\nA possible explanation of the reported modulation was pointed out as originating from the data analysis procedure. A yearly subtraction of the constant component can give rise to a sawtooth residual in the presence of a slower time dependence.<ref>{{cite arxiv\n |author=D. Buttazzo\n |display-authors=etal\n |year=2002\n |title=Annual modulations from secular variations: relaxing DAMA?\n |eprint=2002.00459\n |class=hep-ex\n}}</ref>\n\n==Follow-up==\nDAMA/NaI has been replaced by the new generation experiment, [[DAMA/LIBRA]]. These experiments are carried out by Italian and Chinese researchers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://people.roma2.infn.it/~dama/web/home.html The DAMA Project]\n\n{{Dark matter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DAMA NaI}}\n[[Category:Experiments for dark matter search]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|an experiment||Dama (disambiguation)}} The '''DAMA/NaI experiment'''<ref name=\"rnc\">{{cite journal\n |author=Bernabei, R. \n |display-authors=etal\n |year=2003\n |title=Dark Matter search\n |journal=[[Rivista del Nuovo Cimento]]\n |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=1\n |doi=\n |arxiv=astro-ph/0307403\n |bibcode=2003NCimR..26a...1B }}</ref><ref name=\"perf\">{{cite journal\n |author=Bernabei, R. \n |display-authors=etal\n |year=1999\n |title=Performances of the about 100&nbsp;kg NaI(Tl) set-up of the DAMA experiment at Gran Sasso\n |journal=[[Il Nuovo Cimento A]]\n |volume=112 |issue=6 |pages=545\u2013575\n |doi=10.1007/BF03035868\n |bibcode=1999NCimA.112..545B }}</ref> investigated the presence of [[Dark Matter|dark matter]] particles in the galactic halo by exploiting the model-independent annual modulation signature. Based on the Earth's orbit around the Sun and the solar system's speed with respect to the center of the galaxy (which on short time scales can be considered constant), the [[Earth]] should be exposed to a higher flux of dark matter particles around June&nbsp;2,{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} when its [[orbital speed]] is added to the one of the solar system with respect to the [[galaxy]] and to a smaller one around December&nbsp;2, when the two velocities are subtracted. The annual modulation signature is distinctive since the effect induced by dark matter particles must simultaneously satisfy many requirements.\n\n==Description==\nThe experimental set-up was located deep underground in the [[Laboratori Nazionali del Gran Sasso]] in [[Italy]].\n\nThe experimental set-up was made by nine 9.70&nbsp;kg low-radioactivity scintillating [[thallium]]-doped [[sodium iodide]]  [[crystal]]s [NaI(Tl)]. Each crystal was faced by two low-background [[photomultiplier]]s through 10&nbsp;cm light guides. The detectors were installed inside a sealed copper box flushed with highly pure nitrogen in order to insulate the detectors from air that contains trace amounts of radon, a radioactive gas. To reduce the natural environmental background the copper box is enclosed inside a multicomponent multi-ton passive shield made of copper, lead, polyethylene/paraffin, cadmium foil. A [[Poly(methyl methacrylate)|plexiglas]] box encloses the whole shield and is also kept in a highly pure nitrogen atmosphere. A concrete [[neutron]] moderator 1&nbsp;m thick largely surrounds the set-up.\n\n==Results==\nThe DAMA/NaI set-up observed the annual modulation signature over 7&nbsp;annual cycles (1995\u20132002). The presence of a model independent positive evidence in the data of DAMA/NaI was first reported by the DAMA collaboration in fall&nbsp;1997 and published beginning of 1998.<ref name=\"mod1\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=1998 |title=Searching for WIMPs by the annual modulation signature |journal=[[Physics Letters B]] |volume=424 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=195\u2013201 |doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(98)00172-5 |bibcode=1998PhLB..424..195B}}</ref> The final paper with the full results was published in 2003 after the end of experiment in July&nbsp;2002.<ref name=\"rnc\" /> Various corollary investigations are continuing and have also been published.<ref name=\"sisd\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2001 |title=Investigating the DAMA annual modulation data in a mixed coupling framework |journal=[[Physics Letters B]] |volume=509 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=197\u2013203 |doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(01)00493-2 |bibcode=2001PhLB..509..197B }}</ref><ref name=\"inel\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2002 |title=Investigating the DAMA annual modulation data in the framework of inelastic dark matter |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=61\u201364 |doi=10.1007/s100520100854 |bibcode=2002EPJC...23...61B }}</ref><ref name=\"halo\">{{cite journal |author1=Belli, P. |display-authors=etal |year=2002 |title=Effect of the galactic halo modeling on the DAMA-NaI annual modulation result: An extended analysis of the data for weakly interacting massive particles with a purely spin-independent coupling |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=66 |issue=4 |pages=043503 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.66.043503 |arxiv=hep-ph/0203242 |bibcode=2002PhRvD..66d3503B}}</ref><ref name=\"ijmpd\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2004 |title=Dark matter particles in the galactic halo: Results and implications from DAMA/NaI |journal=[[International Journal of Modern Physics D]] |volume=13 |issue=10 |pages=2127\u20132159 |doi=10.1142/S0218271804006619 |arxiv=astro-ph/0501412 |bibcode=2004IJMPD..13.2127B }}</ref><ref name=\"ijmpa\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2006 |title=Investigating pseudoscalar and scalar dark matter |journal=[[International Journal of Modern Physics A]] |volume=21 |issue=7 |pages=1445\u20131469 |doi=10.1142/S0217751X06030874 |arxiv=astro-ph/0511262 |bibcode=2006IJMPA..21.1445B }}</ref><ref name=\"sag\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2006 |title=Investigating halo substructures with annual modulation signature |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=47 |issue= 1|pages=263\u2013271 |doi=10.1140/epjc/s2006-02559-9 |arxiv=astro-ph/0604303 |bibcode=2006EPJC...47..263B }}</ref><ref name=\"migdal\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2007 |title=On electromagnetic contributions in WIMP quests  |journal=[[International Journal of Modern Physics A]] |volume=22 |issue=19 |pages=3155\u20133168 |doi=10.1142/S0217751X07037093 |arxiv=0706.1421 |bibcode= 2007IJMPA..22.3155B}}</ref><ref name=\"wimpele\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2008 |title=Investigating electron interacting dark matter  |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=3155\u20133168 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.77.023506 |arxiv=0706.1421 |bibcode=2008PhRvD..77b3506B }}</ref><ref name=\"chan\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2008 |title=Possible implications of the channeling effect in NaI(Tl) crystals |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=53 |issue=2 |pages=205\u2013213 |doi=10.1140/epjc/s10052-007-0479-0 |arxiv=0710.0288 |bibcode=2008EPJC...53..205B}}</ref><ref name=\"ldm\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2008 |title=Investigation on light dark matter |journal=[[Modern Physics Letters A]] |volume=23 |issue=26 |pages=2125\u20132140 |doi=10.1142/S0217732308027473 |arxiv=0802.4336 |bibcode=2008MPLA...23.2125B }}</ref>\n\nThe model-independent evidence is compatible with a wide set of scenarios regarding the nature of the dark matter candidate and related astrophysical, nuclear and [[Particle Physics|particle physics]],<ref name=\"foot\">{{cite journal |author=Foot, R. |year=2004 |title=Reconciling the positive DAMA annual modulation signal with the negative results of the CDMS&nbsp;II experiment |journal=[[Modern Physics Letters A]] |volume=19 |issue=24 |pages=1841\u20131846 |doi=10.1142/S0217732304015051 |arxiv=astro-ph/0405362 |bibcode=2004MPLA...19.1841F }}</ref> for example: [[Neutralino|neutralinos]],<ref name=\"bot1\">{{cite journal |author1=Bottino, A. |display-authors=etal |year=2003 |title=Light Relic Neutralinos |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=67 |issue=6 |pages=063519 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.67.063519 |arxiv=hep-ph/0212379 |bibcode=2003PhRvD..67f3519B}}</ref><ref name=\"bot2\">{{cite journal |author1=Bottino, A. |display-authors=etal |year=2003 |title=Lower bound on the neutralino mass from new data on CMB and implications for relic neutralinos |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=043506 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.68.043506 |arxiv=hep-ph/0304080  |bibcode=2003PhRvD..68d3506B}}</ref><ref name=\"bot3\">{{cite journal |author1=Bottino, A. |display-authors=etal |year=2004 |title=Light neutralinos and WIMP direct searches  |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=69 |issue=3 |pages=037302 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.69.037302 |arxiv=hep-ph/0307303 |bibcode=2004PhRvD..69c7302B}}</ref> inelastic dark matter,<ref name=\"smit\">{{cite journal |author1=Smith, D.T. |author2=Weiner, N. |year=2005 |title=The Status of Inelastic Dark Matter |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=72 |pages=063509 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.72.063509 |arxiv=hep-ph/0402065 |bibcode=2005PhRvD..72f3509T |issue=6}}</ref> [[self-interacting dark matter]],<ref name=\"mitr\">{{cite journal |author=Mitra, S.  |year=2005 |title=Has Dama Detected Self-Interacting Dark Matter? |journal=[[Physical Review D]] |volume=71 |issue=12 |pages=121302 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.71.121302 |arxiv=astro-ph/0409121 |bibcode=2005PhRvD..71l1302M }}</ref> and heavy 4th&nbsp;generation [[Neutrino|neutrinos]],<ref name=\"belo1\">{{cite journal |author1=Belotsky, K.M. |author2=Damour, T. |author3=Khlopov, M. Yu. |year=2002 |title=Implications of a solar-system population of massive 4th&nbsp;generation neutrinos for underground searches of monochromatic neutrino-annihilation signals |journal=[[Physics Letters B]] |volume=529 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=10\u201318 |doi=10.1016/S0370-2693(02)01234-0 |arxiv=astro-ph/0201314 |bibcode=2002PhLB..529...10B}}</ref><ref name=\"belo2\">{{cite journal |author1=Belotsky, K. |author2=Fargion, D. |author3=Khlopov, M. |author4=Konoplich, R.V. |year=2008 |title=May Heavy neutrinos solve underground and cosmic ray puzzles? |journal=[[Physics of Atomic Nuclei]] |volume=71 |issue=1 |pages=147\u2013161 |doi=10.1007/s11450-008-1016-9 |arxiv=hep-ph/0411093 |bibcode=2008PAN....71..147B}}</ref>\n\nA careful quantitative investigation of possible sources of systematic and side reactions has been regularly carried out and published at the time of each data release.<ref name=\"sist\">{{cite journal |author1=Bernabei, R. |display-authors=etal |year=2000 |title=On the investigation of possible systematics in WIMP annual modulation search |journal=[[European Physical Journal C]] |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=283\u2013292 |doi=10.1007/s100520000540 |bibcode=2000EPJC...18..283B}}</ref> No systematic effect or side reaction able to account for the observed modulation amplitude and to simultaneously satisfy all the requirements of the signature has been found.\n\nThe experiment has also obtained and published many results on other processes and/or approaches.\n\n==Skepticism==\nNegative results from the [[XENON Dark Matter Search Experiment]] seem to contradict DAMA/Nal's results.<ref name=sciamer>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=dama-dark-matter |title=WIMP Wars: Astronomers and physicists remain skeptical of long-standing dark matter claim |last=Matson |first=John |date=6 May 2011 |magazine=Scientific American |access-date=12 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Korea Invisible Mass Search#COSINE|COSINE-100]] collaboration has been working in Korea towards confirming or refuting the DAMA-signal. They are using similar experimental setup to DAMA (NaI(Ti)-crystals). They published their results in December 2018 in the journal Nature; their conclusion was that their \"result rules out WIMP\u2013nucleon interactions as the cause of the annual modulation observed by the DAMA collaboration\". <ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/s41586-018-0739-1|pmid = 30518890| title=An experiment to search for dark-matter interactions using sodium iodide detectors| journal=Nature| volume=564| issue=7734| pages=83\u201386| year=2018| author1=COSINE-100 Collaboration| bibcode=2018Natur.564...83C| last2=Adhikari| first2=Govinda| last3=Adhikari| first3=Pushparaj| last4=Barbosa De Souza| first4=Estella| last5=Carlin| first5=Nelson| last6=Choi| first6=Seonho| last7=Djamal| first7=Mitra| last8=Ezeribe| first8=Anthony C.| last9=Ha| first9=Chang Hyon| last10=Hahn| first10=Insik| last11=Hubbard| first11=Antonia J. F.| last12=Jeon| first12=Eunju| last13=Jo| first13=Jay Hyun| last14=Joo| first14=Hanwool| last15=Kang| first15=Woon Gu| last16=Kang| first16=Woosik| last17=Kauer| first17=Matthew| last18=Kim| first18=Bonghee| last19=Kim| first19=Hongjoo| last20=Kim| first20=Hyounggyu| last21=Kim| first21=Kyungwon| last22=Kim| first22=Nam Young| last23=Kim| first23=Sun Kee| last24=Kim| first24=Yeongduk| last25=Kim| first25=Yong-Hamb| last26=Ko| first26=Young Ju| last27=Kudryavtsev| first27=Vitaly Y.| last28=Lee| first28=Hyun Su| last29=Lee| first29=Jaison| last30=Lee| first30=Jooyoung| displayauthors=29|arxiv = 1906.01791}}</ref>\n\nA possible explanation of the reported modulation was pointed out as originating from the data analysis procedure. A yearly subtraction of the constant component can give rise to a sawtooth residual in the presence of a slower time dependence.<ref>{{cite arxiv\n |author=D. Buttazzo\n |display-authors=etal\n |year=2002\n |title=Annual modulations from secular variations: relaxing DAMA?\n |eprint=2002.00459\n |class=hep-ex\n}}</ref>\n\n==Follow-up==\nDAMA/NaI has been replaced by the new generation experiment, [[DAMA/LIBRA]]. These experiments are carried out by Italian and Chinese researchers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://people.roma2.infn.it/~dama/web/home.html The DAMA Project]\n\n{{Dark matter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DAMA NaI}}\n[[Category:Experiments for dark matter search]]\n", "name_user": "Rickinasia", "label": "safe", "comment": "Internal link to other Wiki page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DAMA/NaI"}
{"title_page": "Complementary currency", "text_new": "A '''complementary currency''' is a [[currency]] or [[medium of exchange]] that is not necessarily a national currency, but that is thought of as supplementing or complementing national currencies.{{r|\"ccto\"|page=3}}{{r|ccg2006|page=2}}  Complementary currencies are usually not [[legal tender]] and their use is  based on agreement between the parties exchanging the currency. According to J\u00e9r\u00f4me Blanc of Laboratoire d'\u00c9conomie de la Firme et des Institutions, complementary currencies aim to protect, stimulate or orientate the economy.{{r|cc|page=7}} They may also be used to advance particular social, environmental, or political goals.{{r|hal|page=4}}\n\nWhen speaking about complementary currencies, a number of overlapping and often interchangeable terms are in use: [[Local currency|local]] or [[Community currency|community]] currencies are complementary currencies used within a locality or other form of community (such as business-based or online communities); regional currencies are similar to local currencies, but are used within a larger geographical region; and [[sectoral currency|sectoral]] currencies are complementary currencies used within a single economic sector, such as education or health care. Many [[private currencies]] are complementary currencies issued by private businesses or organizations. Other terms include '''alternative currency''', [[auxiliary currencies|auxiliary currency]], and microcurrency. [[Mutual credit]] is a form of alternative currency, and thus any form of lending that does not go through the banking system can be considered a form of alternative currency. [[Barter]]s are another type of alternative currency. These are actually exchange systems, which trade only items, without the use of any currency whatsoever. Finally, [[Local Exchange Trading Systems|LETS]] is a special form of barter that trades points for items. One point stands for one worker-hour of work, and is thus a [[Time-based currency]].\n\n==Purposes==\nCurrent complementary currencies have often been designed intentionally to address specific issues, for example to increase financial stability.{{r|crisis}} Most complementary currencies have multiple purposes and/or are intended to address multiple issues. They can be useful for communities that do not have access to financial capital, and for adjusting peoples' spending behavior.{{r|boot}} The 2006 Annual Report of the Worldwide Database of Complementary Currency Systems presented a survey of 150 complementary currency systems in which 94 respondents said that \"all reasons\" were selected, among cooperation, micro/small/medium enterprise development, activating the local market, reducing the need for national currency, and community development.{{r|\"DeMeulenaere\"}}\n\nAims may include:\n* lifeboat currencies{{Technical statement|date=November 2019}}\n* to increase financial stability{{r|crisis}}\n* to reduce carbon emissions, by encouraging localisation of trade and relationships\n* to encouraging use of under-used resources{{r|ccg2006|page=2}}\n* to recognise the informal economy\n* promote local businesses\n\n===Advantages===\nSome alternative currencies devalue rapidly (they are called Schwundgeld); this increases monetary circulation. The [[Miracle of W\u00f6rgl]] is an event that showed the potential of this increased spending through the introduction of a local currency known as [[Freigeld]]. Local currencies also have the benefit that they cannot be spent abroad, and thus the [[money]] always keeps circulating locally, benefiting only the local economy.\n\nAlternative currencies are reported to work as a counterbalance for the local economy. They increase in activity if the local economy slows down, and decrease in activity if the local economy goes up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stodder|first=James|title=Implications for Macroeconomic Stability|url=http://www.lietaer.com/images/Stodder_Reciprocal_Exchange.pdf|accessdate=3 April 2014|date=January 2005}}</ref>{{Dubious|No mention of alternative currency|reason=No mention of alternative currency|date=June 2015}}\n\nAs a commercial tool within a business, as opposed to a geographical social tool, a complementary currency can open a business up to a preferred source marketplace whereby they can sell their otherwise devalued or worthless spare capacity in exchange for the complementary currency. By selling their spare capacity (empty hotel rooms / under utilised staff hours / blank diary slots / excess stock) the business is able to harness the otherwise lost value gaining some key benefits such as :- Improved profits; stronger balance sheet; enhanced cash flow; more customers and a growth in market share.\n\n===Disadvantages===\nAlternative currencies promoted as [[local currencies]] which cannot be spent outside the community have limited use.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nAccording to professor Nikolaus L\u00e4ufer, the use of local currencies such as Freigeld can only increase economic activity temporarily. Lengthy use of a local currency will ultimately result in a decline in economic activity and lead to a destabilization of the economy. This is due to the increased circulation velocity of the money as the amount in circulation decreases (as currencies as Freigeld reduce in value rapidly).<ref>{{cite web|last=L\u00e4ufer|first=Nikolaus|title=Natural Economic Order Theories or Freiwirtschaftslehre (Silvio Gesell)|url=http://www.uni-konstanz.de/FuF/wiwi/laufer/main.html#FREI|publisher=University of Konstanz|accessdate=3 April 2014||date= 31 December 2006|language=German}}</ref>{{ clarify | date = June 2015 | reason = More specific link required}}\n\n==Tax==\n{{Expand section|section=2|date=May 2019}}\nOften there are issues related to paying [[tax]]. Some alternative currencies are considered tax-exempt, but most of them are fully taxed as if they were national currency, with the caveat that the tax must be paid in the national currency. The legality and tax-status of alternative currencies varies widely from country to country; some systems in use in some countries would be illegal in others.\n\n==Types==\nComplementary currencies describe a wide group of exchange systems, currencies or [[scrip]]s designed to be used in combination with standard currencies or other complementary currencies. They can be valued and exchanged in relationship to national currencies but also function as [[Medium of exchange|media of exchange]] on their own. Complementary currencies lie outside the nationally defined legal realm of [[legal tender]] and are not used as such. Rate of exchange, scope of circulation and use in combination with other currencies differs greatly between complementary currency systems, as is the case with national currency systems.\n\n[[File:Freigeld1.jpg|thumb|One [[W\u00f6rgl]] Schilling note with [[Demurrage (currency)|demurrage]] stamps]]\nSome complementary currencies incorporate value scales based on time or the backing of real resources (gold, oil, services, etc.). A [[time-based currency]] is valued by the time required to perform a service in hours, notwithstanding the potential market value of the service. Another type of complementary monetary systems is the barter, an exchange of specific goods or services is performed without the use of any currency.\n\nIn 1982, the most widespread auxiliary currency system, the [[Local Exchange Trading Systems]], was created. It regulates the exchange of goods and services between the members of the cooperative. Examples for an investment system of complementary currency are the Automatic Social Financial Network (ASFN) and the international [[crowdsourcing]] and [[crowd-funding]] community Evolution RA<ref>http://asfn.info/en/</ref> whose members use their own complementary virtual currency \"\u0421yber-gold\". The introductory fee paid by the new association members is subsequently directed toward investments in a variety of commercial projects.\n\nSome complementary currencies take advantage of [[Demurrage (currency)|demurrage]] fees, an intentional devaluation of the currency over time, like negative [[interest]]. This stimulates market exchanges in the devaluating currency, propagates new participation in the currency system and forces the storage of wealth (hoarding) ability usually reserved for currency into more permanent and better value-holding tools like property, improvement, education, technology, health, equity securities, etc., all of which are sheltered from the currency-based demurrage fees.\n\nOther experimental complementary currencies use high interest fees to promote heavy competition between participants, and the removal of wealth from long term wealth holding structures (natural/material wealth, property, etc.) to aid in the process of rapid industrialization, mass production, automation and competitive innovation.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nMonetary speculation and gambling are usually outside the design parameters of complementary currencies. Complementary currencies are often intentionally restricted in their regional spread, time of validity or sector of use and may require a membership of participating individuals or points of acceptance.\n\nThere are some complementary currencies that are regional or global, such as the [[Community Exchange System]], [[WIR]] and Friendly Favors, Tibex in the [[Lazio]] region in Italy or the proposed global currency [[Terra (currency)|terra]].{{r|rietaer}}\n\nA [[community currency]] is a type of complementary currency that has the explicit aim to support and build more equal, connected and sustainable societies. A community currency is designed to be used by a specific group.{{r|CCIA}}\n\n==Activists==\nSome complementary currency activists are Belgian ex-banker [[Bernard Lietaer]], British economist Hazel Henderson, Dutch STRO-director [[Henk van Arkel]] that developed [[Cyclos]], [[Qoin]] initiators [[Edgar Kampers]] and [[Rob van Hilten]], [[Paul Glover (activist)|Paul Glover]] of Ithaca HOURS, [[Margrit Kennedy]] from Monneta, [[Local exchange trading system|LETSystem]] inventor [[Michael Linton]], [[Time Banking]] inventor [[Edgar S. Cahn]], [[Complementary Currency Resource Center]] coordinator [[Stephen DeMeulenaere]] and many others. Lietaer has argued that the world's national currencies are inadequate for the world's business needs, citing how 87 countries have experienced major currency crashes over a 20-year period, and arguing for complementary currencies as a way to protect against these problems.<ref>[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-21825746_ITM \"Bernard Lietaer Urges the Growth of New Currency\", ''Bank Technology News'', Jul. 1st, 2004.]</ref> Lietaer has also spoken at an [[International Reciprocal Trade Association]] (IRTA) conference about [[barter]].<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2005/07/prweb264099.htm \"Barter and Cashless Trading Summit to Promote Collaboration of International Reciprocal Trade: IRTAs 26th Annual Conference Is The First of Its Kind\", ''PRWEB'', Jul. 22nd, 2005.]</ref>\n\n==List of complementary currencies==\n{{Merge|Local currency#List of local currencies|date=November 2019|section=yes}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Name \n!scope=\"col\"| Type\n!scope=\"col\"| Country\n!scope=\"col\"| Region\n!scope=\"col\"| Active \n!scope=\"col\"| Website\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Brixton Pound]]\n| Local currency\n| United Kingdom\n| Europe\n|2009\u2013present\n|[http://brixtonpound.org/what brixtonpound.org]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Bristol Pound]]\n| Local currency\n| United Kingdom\n| Europe\n|2009\u2013present\n|[https://bristolpound.org bristolpound.org]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[BerkShares]]\n| Local currency\n| United States\n| North America\n| 2006\u2013present\n| [http://berkshares.org/ berkshares.org]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Baltimore BNote\n|\n| United States\n| North America\n| \n| [http