sher=Global Community Initiatives|accessdate=18 June 2015|date=2006}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ccto\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090612090715/http://www.elecan.net/docs/moned/ccto.pdf Costanza, Robert et al., \"Complementary Currencies as a Method to Improve Local Sustainable Economic Welfare\", University of Vermont, Draft, 12 December 2003.]</ref>\n\n<ref name=CCIA>{{cite web|title=People Powered Money: designing, developing and delivering community currencies|url=http://www.neweconomics.org/page/-/publications/ppm__digital.pdf|publisher=Community Currencies in Action|accessdate=17 June 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=hal>{{cite web|last1=Fare|first1=Marie| last2=Ahmed|first2=Pepita Ould| title=The complementary currency systems: a tricky issue for economists |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/ird-01081350/document|publisher=hal.archives-ouvertes.fr |year=2014 |accessdate=18 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=rietaer>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120217004625/http://sciencelinks.jp/j-east/article/200214/000020021402A0521947.php B. Rietaer, \"Global Complementally Currency: Making Money Sustainable\", ''Environmental Research Quarterly'', Vol. 125, pp. 53\u201359, 2002.]</ref>\n\n<ref name=C3>{{cite web|title=Making Money for Business: Currencies, Profit, and Long-Term Thinking|url=http://www.thesolutionsjournal.com/node/992|publisher=thesolutionsjournal.com|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Sardex>{{cite web|title=Sardex homepage|url=http://www.sardex.net/|publisher=sardex.net|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=RT1>{{cite web|title=Fizet\u0151eszk\u00f6z lesz a R\u00e1bak\u00f6zi Tall\u00e9r|url=http://www.kisalfold.hu/rabakozi_hirek/fizetoeszkoz_lesz_a_rabakozi_taller/2175652/|publisher=kisalfold.hu|accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ven>{{cite web|title=The dollar alternatives - Ven|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2010/fortune/1007/gallery.Alternate_Currency.fortune/4.html|work=cnn.com|publisher=Cable News Network|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> \n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Paul Glover (activist)|Glover, Paul]]. ''Hometown Money: how to enrich your community with local currency.''  Greenplanners, 2013.\n* [[Thomas H. Greco, Jr.|Greco, Thomas H. Jr.]] ''Money: understanding and creating alternatives to legal tender''. White River Junction, Vt: Chelsea Green Publishing, 2001.\n* [[Bernard Lietaer|Lietaer, Bernard]]. ''The Future of Money''. Random House, 2001.\n*  Raddon, M. ''Community and money: men and women making change''. Montreal: Black Rose Books, 2003.\n* Suhr, Dieter (1990). [http://userpage.fu-berlin.de/~roehrigw/suhr/nngengl.html The Neutral Money Network (NeuMoNe): A Critical Analysis of Traditional Money and the Financial Innovation \"Neutral Money\"]\n\n==External links==\n{{External links|date=November 2019}}\n* ''[http://ccmag.net/ Community Currency Magazine]''\n* ''[http://www.uea.ac.uk/env/ijccr/ International Journal of Community Currency Research]''\n* [http://www.complementarycurrency.org/ccDatabase/les_public.html Online Database of Complementary Currencies Worldwide]\n* [http://www.socialtrade.org Social Trade Organisation]\n* [http://secure-exchange-protocols.org/ Secure eXchange Protocols]\n* [http://www.tradenow.gr/HowItWorks.aspx?lang=en Trade Point: Internal currency of Barter platform]\n*{{dmoz|Science/Social_Sciences/Economics/Financial_Economics/Currency_and_Money/Alternative_Monetary_Systems|Alternative Monetary Systems}}\n\n{{Cryptocurrencies}}\n{{Means of Exchange}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Complementary Currency}}\n[[Category:Local currencies]]\n[[Category:Monetary reform]]\n[[Category:Alternative currencies| ]]\n[[Category:Cryptocurrencies]]\n\n[[it:Valuta complementare]]\n", "name_user": "Atotsm", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added the words: not necessarily - Because the WIR is one example of a complementary currency one being national. Therefor: not necessarily.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complementary_currency"}
{"title_page": "Billy McNeill", "text_new": "{{for|the former ice hockey player|Billy McNeill (ice hockey)}}\n{{short description|Scottish footballer and manager}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Mo leister \n| image          = Mcneill.jpg\n| image_size     = 250\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Peter file as Celtic manager in September 1982\n| fullname       = William McNeill<ref name=lhscot>[http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/williammcneill.html Billy McNeill], londonhearts.com</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=y|1940|3|2}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bellshill]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=y|2019|4|22|1940|3|2}}\n| death_place    = [[Newton Mearns]], Scotland\n| height         = {{height|m=1.87}}\n| position       = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    = {{0|0000}}\u20131957\n| youthclubs1    = [[Blantyre Victoria F.C.|Blantyre Victoria]]\n| years1         = 1957\u20131975\n| clubs1         = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n| caps1          = 486\n| goals1         = 22\n| nationalyears1 = 1960\u20131962<ref>[http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu23/player.php?playerid=68 Scotland U23 player McNeill, Billy], FitbaStats</ref>\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-23 football team|Scotland U23]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 5\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1961<ref name=scot60s>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lITgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT215&lpg=PT215&dq=1964+%22scotland+XI%22+v+%22scottish+league|title=Scotland in the 60s: The Definitive Account of the Scottish National Football Side During the 1960s|author=Ronnie McDevitt|year=2016|publisher=Pitch Publishing|isbn=9781785312458}}</ref>\n| nationalteam2 = [[List of Scottish Football League representative players#Scotland trial matches / SFL Centenary players|SFA trial v SFL]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1961\u20131967\n| nationalteam3  = [[Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 9\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 1961\u20131972\n| nationalteam4  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 29\n| nationalgoals4 = 3\n| manageryears1  = 1977\n| manageryears2  = 1977\u20131978\n| manageryears3  = 1978\u20131983\n| manageryears4  = 1983\u20131986\n| manageryears5  = 1986\u20131987\n| manageryears6  = 1987\u20131991\n| manageryears7  = 1998\n| managerclubs1  = [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]\n| managerclubs2  = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n| managerclubs3  = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n| managerclubs4  = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| managerclubs5  = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n| managerclubs6  = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n| managerclubs7  = [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] ([[caretaker manager|caretaker]])\n}}\n'''William McNeill''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}} (2 March 1940 \u2013 22 April 2019) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Association football|football]] player and [[manager (association football)|manager]]. He had a long association with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], spanning more than sixty years as a player, manager and club ambassador. McNeill captained Celtic's '[[Lisbon Lions]]' to their [[European Cup]] victory in [[1967 European Cup Final|1967]] and later spent two spells as the club's manager. As a player and manager, he won 31 major trophies with Celtic.\n\nA defender, McNeill played for Celtic for his entire senior career, and holds the club record for most appearances, a total of 822 games over 18 seasons. He was captain during their most successful era in the 1960s and 70s. The club won nine consecutive [[list of Scottish football champions|Scottish league championships]] and thirteen other major domestic trophies in this time, and in 1967 became the first British club to win the European Cup. He also played 29 times for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].\n\nMcNeill managed Celtic for nine seasons, from 1978 to 1983 and 1987 to 1991, winning four Scottish league championships. This included a league and cup double in 1987\u201388, the club's centenary season. He also managed [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]], [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. In 2015, Celtic installed a statue outside [[Celtic Park]] of McNeill holding aloft the European Cup, an iconic image in their history.\n\n==Early life==\nMcNeill was born on 2 March 1940 in [[Bellshill]], [[Lanarkshire]]. His father was a soldier in the [[Black Watch]] and later the [[Army Physical Training Corps]]. Aged nine, McNeill moved to [[Hereford]] in England where his father was posted, and stayed for two and a half years. Although he already liked football, he enjoyed playing [[rugby union]] in his time there.<ref name=\"HailCesar\">McNeill, B., 2014. ''Hail Cesar''</ref>\n\nHe moved to [[Motherwell]] and excelled playing football as [[Defender (association football)|centre-half]] at [[Our Lady's High School, Motherwell|Our Lady's High School]]. His schoolboy performances led to him signing for the [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior]] team [[Blantyre Victoria F.C.|Blantyre Victoria]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/23/billy-mcneill-ultimate-one-club-player-helped-celtic-change/|title=Billy McNeill: The ultimate one-club player who helped Celtic change the course of European football|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|date=23 April 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=23 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nMcNeill was signed by Celtic for \u00a3250 in 1957 after then reserve team coach [[Jock Stein]] saw him playing for Scotland schoolboys against England.<ref name=\"Guardianobit\" /> He was given the nickname '''Cesar''' after the actor [[Cesar Romero]].<ref name = \"degree\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12762385.Bhoy_racer|title=Bhoy racer|work=The Herald |publisher=Herald & Times Group|quote=\"Billy's nickname is Cesar,\" the prof told the audience. \"However, this doesn't come from any Roman connections, rather from a movie. In the original [[Ocean's 11]], [[Cesar Romero]] drove the getaway car.|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn his early career, Celtic endured some of their most difficult times, and did not win a trophy for eight years. After Stein became manager in 1965, however, the club's fortunes improved. In the [[1964\u201365 Scottish Cup|1965 Scottish Cup final]], Celtic defeated [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]] 3\u20132, with McNeill scoring the winning goal.<ref>[https://thecelticstar.com/billy-mcneill-celtic-personified/ Billy McNeill \u2013 Celtic Personified], The Celtic Star, 13 July 2018</ref> In that season he was named [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Footballer of the Year]], the first year it was awarded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/scotpoy.html |title=Scotland \u2013 Player of the Year |work= |publisher=RSSSF |first=Alan |last=Brown |date=6 December 2018 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith McNeill as captain, Celtic enjoyed their most successful period, dominating Scottish football and regularly competing in the latter stages of European competitions. They won nine [[list of Scottish football champions|Scottish League championships]] in a row, as well as seven [[Scottish Cup]]s and six [[Scottish League Cup]]s.<ref name=bbcobit>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41685748 |title=Billy McNeill: Former Celtic captain & manager dies aged 79 |work=BBC Sport |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nCeltic's greatest season was in [[1966\u201367 Celtic F.C. season|1966\u201367]], when they won every competition they entered, and were the first club to win five trophies in a single season. As well as a [[Treble (association football)|domestic treble]] and the [[Glasgow Cup]], McNeill led the team to victory in the [[1967 European Cup Final]]. The team, which became known as the '[[Lisbon Lions]]', defeated [[Inter Milan]] 2\u20131 and McNeill (whose [[last-minute goal|last minute]] goal, a characteristic header from a set piece, had ensured progression against [[Vojvodina Novi Sad]] in the quarter-final)<ref>[https://celticunderground.net/late-arrivals-vojvodina-1967/ Late Arrivals - Vojvodina 1967], The Celtic Underground, 23 November 2017</ref> was the first British footballer to lift the trophy.<ref name=bbcluke>{{cite news |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35130550 |title=Billy McNeill: The 'Luke Skywalker of his age' |author=[[Archie Macpherson]] |work=BBC Sport |date=18 December 2015 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing another domestic treble in [[1968\u201369 Celtic F.C. season|1968\u201369]], in which another powerful McNeill headed goal set his team on the way to a 4\u20130 win over great rivals [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in the [[1969 Scottish Cup Final|final of the Scottish Cup]],<ref>[https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/16163023.a-4-0-hampden-defeat-by-celtic-ended-sir-alex-fergusons-time-at-rangers-this-ibrox-teams-careers-are-on-the-line/ \"A 4-0 Hampden defeat by Celtic ended Sir Alex Ferguson's time at Rangers - this Ibrox team's careers are on the line\"], The Herald, 17 April 2018</ref> Celtic again reached the [[1970 European Cup Final|European Cup final in 1970]], this time losing to [[Feyenoord]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec196970.html |title=European Competitions 1969-70 |work= |publisher=RSSSF |first=James M. |last=Ross |date=4 June 2015 |accessdate=23 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\nMcNeill retired as a player in 1975, having made a club record 822{{NoteTag|This total is sometimes given as 790. 822 includes 32 games in minor competitions, including the Glasgow Cup, Drybrough Cup and the Anglo-Scottish Cup.}} appearances for Celtic and never being substituted.<ref name=fscfcplayer/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/apr/23/billy-mcneill-career-player-manager-celtic|title=\u2018His career was incredible\u2019 \u2026 Billy McNeill was a winner as player and manager|last=Wilson|first=Paul|date=23 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He won 29 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], scoring 3 goals, and also played 9 times for the [[Scottish League XI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/williammcneill.html|title=SFL player William McNeill|website=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nAfter retiring as a player, McNeill began coaching [[Celtic Boys Club]]'s under 16 team. He began his management career at [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]] in April 1977, before moving to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] two months later.\n\n===Aberdeen===\nMcNeill was appointed Aberdeen manager in June 1977, having been recommended by Jock Stein.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Grant, Michael & Robertson, Rob. 2011 ''The Management: Scotland's Great Football Bosses''</ref> He succeeded [[Ally MacLeod]].<ref name = \"afc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.afc.co.uk/2019/04/23/in-memoriam-billy-mcneill/ |title=In Memoriam: Billy McNeill |work= |publisher=Aberdeen FC |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> In his one season in charge, 1977\u201378, McNeill led Aberdeen to runners-up finishes in the league and Scottish Cup, and enjoyed a positive working relationship with the club's chairman, Dick Donald.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> Their performance in the league was their best since 1972, and three places above Celtic. During his season with Aberdeen, McNeill signed [[Gordon Strachan]], [[Steve Archibald]] and [[Neil Simpson]].<ref name = \"afc\"/> When Stein retired as Celtic manager, he identified McNeill as his successor, and McNeill accepted the club's offer. He was succeeded at Aberdeen by [[Alex Ferguson]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n===Celtic===\nMcNeill returned to a Celtic side who had finished in fifth place in [[1977\u201378 Celtic F.C. season|1977\u201378]]. He immediately improved the club's fortunes, as they won the league championship in [[1978\u201379 Celtic F.C. season|1978\u201379]]. Celtic clinched the title in their final match of the league season by beating Rangers 4\u20132, despite having had [[Johnny Doyle]] sent off.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/2642?item=2642 |title=When 10 men won the league |work= |publisher=Celtic FC |first=Joe |last=Sullivan |date=21 May 2012 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis five years in charge saw Celtic win three League championships, in 1978-79, 1980\u201381 and 1981\u201382, the Scottish Cup in 1979-80 and the League Cup in 1982\u201383.<ref name=fscfcmanager/> This period saw Celtic's greatest competition come from the [[New Firm (Scotland)|New Firm clubs]] \u2013 Aberdeen, who won the League championship in 1979\u201380, and Dundee United, who won the title in 1982\u201383.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/apr/19/the-forgotten-story-of-dundee-united-glory-years-under-jim-mclean |title=The forgotten story of ... Dundee United's glory years under Jim McLean |first=Daniel |last=Harris |work=The Guardian |publisher= |date=19 April 2017 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nMcNeill is credited with developing young players for Celtic, such as [[Paul McStay]] and [[Charlie Nicholas]], and making signings such as [[Murdo MacLeod]] and [[David Provan (footballer, born 1956)|Davie Provan]] who became key players for the club through the 1980s. However, McNeill found working with Desmond White, Celtic's chairman, very difficult, and felt underpaid and underappreciated. Despite Celtic's successes, by 1983 he was being paid less than the managers of Aberdeen, Dundee United, Rangers and St Mirren. When White sold Nicholas to Arsenal, against McNeill's wishes, McNeill looked for the first available way out, and took up the offer to manage Manchester City.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Manchester City and Aston Villa===\nOn 30 June 1983 he moved to England to manage [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. Two years before being appointed by City, he had been strongly linked with the manager's job at their [[Manchester derby|city rivals]] [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], when [[Ron Atkinson]] was appointed instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ywJBAAAAIBAJ&sjid=i6cMAAAAIBAJ&dq=manchester-united&pg=5156%2C3698360|title=McNeill \u2013 I'm so flattered |first=Alan |last=Davidson |newspaper=Evening Times |date=19 May 1981 |page=32 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> McNeill secured promotion for City after two seasons in charge (in [[1984\u201385 in English football|1984\u201385]]), and oversaw survival in their first season back in the First Division ([[1985\u201386 in English football|1985\u201386]]).<ref name=\"Guardianobit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/apr/23/billy-mcneill-obituary|title=Billy McNeill obituary|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe started the [[1986\u201387 in English football|1986\u201387 season]] as manager of Manchester City, but quit in September 1986 to take charge of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref name=bbcobit/> When Villa were relegated, after finishing bottom of the First Division in May 1987, McNeill stood down and was replaced by [[Graham Taylor (football manager)|Graham Taylor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/aston-villa/9225706/Aston-Villas-form-under-Alex-McLeish-as-bad-as-that-of-the-relegated-squad-under-Billy-McNeill.html|title=Aston Villa's form under Alex McLeish as bad as that of the relegated squad under Billy McNeill|first=Dan|last=Heald|date=25 April 2012|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Manchester City were also relegated that season.\n\n===Return to Celtic===\nHe then returned to Celtic, and in his first season, [[1987\u201388 Celtic F.C. season|1987\u201388]], the club won the League Championship and Scottish Cup double in their centenary year.<ref name=bbcobit/> Celtic were renowned for scoring late goals that season, and in both the Cup semi-final and final scored late goals to come from behind and win 2\u20131. Celtic won the Scottish Cup in [[1988\u201389 Celtic F.C. season|1988\u201389]], defeating Rangers 1\u20130 in the [[1989 Scottish Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scottish_cup/1963032.stm |title=Old Firm finals down the years |work=BBC Sport |date=1 May 2002 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19890522&id=izNAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RlkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3687,251027 |newspaper=The Glasgow Herald |date=22 May 1989 |page=22 |title=Tension and fear spoil show-piece |first=James |last=Traynor |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following two seasons were disappointing, and Celtic did not win a trophy. They lost the [[1990 Scottish Cup Final]] to Aberdeen on penalties. Celtic's league performance was particularly poor; after finishing in third place in 1988-89, they managed only fifth in [[1989\u201390 Celtic F.C. season|1989\u201390]] and third in [[1990\u201391 Celtic F.C. season|1990\u201391]]. This was the beginning of a period of poor results and increasing financial instability for Celtic, which continued until the club was taken over by [[Fergus McCann]] in 1994. McNeill was sacked by Celtic in May 1991 after four seasons as manager, at the age of 51. In two spells he won eight trophies as Celtic manager \u2013 four League championships, three Scottish Cups and one League Cup.<ref name=fscfcmanager/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/alan-mcrae-pays-tribute-to-billy-mcneill/?rid=13925 |title=Alan McRae pays tribute to Billy McNeill |work= |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving Celtic he turned down several offers to return to management, including from [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], and worked in the media instead. He remained bitter about the manner of his departure from Celtic, until he was asked to become a club ambassador in 2009.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Hibernian===\n\nMcNeill had a brief spell as [[director of football|football development manager]]{{NoteTag|McNeill's position at Hibernian has been described in different sources as \"football development manager\", \"football development officer\" and \"director of development\".}} at [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in the later part of the [[1997\u201398 Hibernian F.C. season|1997\u201398]] season.<ref name = \"hibs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hibernianfc.co.uk/news/9906 |title=Billy McNeill |work= |publisher=Hibernian FC |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> He was brought in as a mentor to manager [[Jim Duffy (footballer)|Jim Duffy]],<ref name = \"hibs\"/> as they unsuccessfully attempted to arrest a decline in fortunes at the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-millar-two-hot-for-hibs-1140871.html |title=Football: Millar two hot for Hibs |work=The Independent |date=25 January 1998 |accessdate=}}</ref> McNeill took charge of the team for one game after Duffy was sacked, even though he had been out of football since leaving Celtic in 1991 and was recovering from heart surgery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-miller-helps-miller-to-wind-up-hibernian-1143676.html |title=Football: Miller helps Miller to wind up Hibernian |work=The Independent |date=8 February 1998 |accessdate=}}</ref> He left Hibernian at the end of the 1997\u201398 season.<ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102023430/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-18668667.html |title=Article: McNeill's departure inevitable |work=The Scotsman |publisher= |date=16 July 1998 |accessdate= |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-18668667.html |archivedate=2 November 2012 |first=Simon |last=Pia}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nMcNeill wrote three autobiographies:\n* {{cite book | last1 = McNeill | first1 = Billy | title = For Celtic and Scotland | publisher = The Sportmans Book Club | location = | year = 1966 | isbn = }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = McNeill | first1 = Billy | last2 = Cameron | first2 = Alex | title = Back to Paradise | publisher = Mainstream | location = | year = 1988 | isbn = 978-1851581887 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = McNeill | first1 = Billy | title = Hail Cesar | publisher = Headline | location = | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0755313167 }}\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n[[File:Billy McNeil statue at Celtic Park (geograph 5647921).jpg|thumb|[[John McKenna (sculptor)|John McKenna]]'s statue of McNeill outside [[Celtic Park]]]]\n\nMcNeill was awarded the [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in November 1974. In 2002 he was voted Celtic's greatest ever captain, and a member of Celtic's greatest team, by the club's fans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/2245965.stm|title=Jinky best-ever Celtic player|date=9 September 2002|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]] in 2002<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2530591.stm |title=The names in the Hall of Fame |work=BBC News |date=30 November 2002 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> and the [[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfootballmuseum.org.uk/hall-of-fame/2004.html |title=2004 |publisher=[[Scottish Football Museum]] |accessdate=17 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928040649/http://www.scottishfootballmuseum.org.uk/hall-of-fame/2004.html |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015 Celtic installed a statue at the entrance to the Celtic Way outside [[Celtic Park]], created by sculptor [[John McKenna (sculptor)|John McKenna]]. The statue, in bronze on a granite base, shows McNeill holding aloft the European Cup, an iconic image in the club's history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/9763 |title=Celtic unveil statue in honour of legend Billy McNeill |work= |publisher=Celtic FC |date=19 December 2015 |accessdate=23 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he was recognised with a '[[List of one-club men in association football#Special award|One Club Man]]' award by Spanish club [[Athletic Bilbao]] for his achievements and loyalty to Celtic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47950885 |title=Celtic: Billy McNeill awarded Athletic Bilbao honour |work=BBC Sport |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/2019/04/16/billy-mcneill-y-malin-monstrom-premiados-por-el-athletic-como-one-club-awards |title=Billy McNeill and Malin Mostr\u00f6m, awarded by Athletic as One Club Awards |work= |publisher=Athletic Bilbao |date=16 April 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\nA short time after his death, the new sports pitch at his former school, Our Lady's High, was named in his honour.<ref>[https://www.motherwelltimes.co.uk/education/school-sports-park-named-after-football-great-billy-mcneill-1-4944517/amp School sports park named after football great Billy McNeill], Motherwell Times, 10 June 2019</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcNeill's maternal grandparents were from Lithuania.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FJWWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT18&lpg=PT18&dq=billy+mcneill+lithuania&source=bl&ots=Y2F7mxcaXQ&sig=LZ-C4nDqZZk8lz3Sh6UvEbjnLQE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjg7q6O_bDSAhXsAcAKHZVGB244FBDoAQhHMAg#v=onepage&q=billy%20mcneill%20lithuania&f=false |title=Hail Cesar|quote=My Lithuanian grandparents boarded an immigrant ship believing that they were bound for the New World, but instead of landing in New York they disembarked at Leith|first=Billy|last=McNeill|year=2004|isbn=978-1-4722-2699-0|publisher=Headline Publishing Group|location=London}}</ref> He was Catholic.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/billy-mcneill-obituary-dr2tgpblj</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2019/04/23/billy-mcneill-giant-scottish-football-celtic-captain-led-lisbon/</ref>\n\nMcNeill married Liz Callaghan, a dancer on the TV variety show ''[[The White Heather Club]]'' in 1963. They had five children.<ref name=\"Guardianobit\"/>\n\nMcNeill, along with former Rangers player [[Eric Caldow]], stood as a candidate for the [[Scottish Senior Citizens Unity Party]] in the [[2003 Scottish Parliament election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2893699.stm |title='Old' firm legends seek votes|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=27 March 2003 |accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref> In 2008, he was awarded an honorary degree from the [[University of Glasgow]].<ref name=\"degree\"/>\n\nIt was reported in February 2017 that McNeill was suffering from [[dementia]] and was very limited in his speech.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-39095623|title=Family of Billy McNeill confirm he has dementia|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=26 February 2017|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> He died on 22 April 2019, aged 79.<ref name=\"Guardianobit\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/16059 |title=Family\u2019s immense sadness as Celtic legend Billy McNeill passes away |work= |publisher=Celtic FC |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=bbcobit/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season !! Club !! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Scotland\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Scottish Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | 